<TEXT>
fbi agents seized documents at a plant where 
northrop corp builds parts for the b2 stealth bomber a northrop 
spokesman said thursday 
the spokesman tony cantafio said the company previously has 
turned over thousands of documents in connection with civil 
lawsuits over alleged fraud in the b2 program 
in another blow to the b2 program thursday congress heard a 
recommendation that spending for the radarevading plane should be 
scaled back because of doubts about the planes ability to pass 
critical tests 
the general accounting office the investigative arm of 
congress cautioned that spending cuts shouldnt be imposed until 
after a study to ensure that slowing the program wouldnt result in 
higher costs in the long run 
frank c conahan assistant comptroller general and a member of 
the gao told the house armed services committee that the pentagon 
should work with contractors to find out what the real cost would 
be to delay this and if it isnt an awful lot than i think i 
would concur in that decision to delay this airplane 
cantafio said he didnt know why the agents raided the factory 
in the pico rivera section of los angeles on feb 15 as part of the 
criminal probe rather than subpoena the documents 
they showed up with a search warrant i dont know why they 
wont say they were there cantafio said they came in and took 
some documents on the b2 
he refused to describe the documents and spokesmen for the fbi 
in los angeles and justice department in washington didnt 
immediately return telephone calls 
the los angeles times cited unidentified sources as saying the 
raid provides evidence that a justice department criminal 
investigation into the 70 billion program is escalating after more 
than a year 
several civil and criminal investigations of northrop are under 
way former employees of the century citybased aerospace company 
have filed a whistleblower lawsuit against northrop seeking 20 
billion in damages because of alleged civil fraud in the b2 
program 
the b2 is intended to be difficult to detect on enemy radar 
the effect is achieved through use of fiberglasslike composite 
materials rather than metal as well as a configuration with few 
angles or protruding parts 
