<TEXT>
a man who embezzled 2 million in us 
department of housing and urban development funds to pay for a 
lavish lifestyle pleaded guilty to reduced charges wednesday after 
helping the government win a cocaine case 
cy walker who spent at least 180000 on cars and also bought a 
speedboat furs and jewelry with some of the stolen hud money 
pleaded guilty to one count of embezzlement and one count of 
failing to file an income tax return for 1986 
us attorney jim wilson said walker faces maximum penalties of 
five years in prison and a 250000 fine on the embezzlement count 
and one year in prison and a 25000 fine on the tax return count 
walker who once held the hud contract to handle closings of hud 
property in the montgomery area is to be sentenced by us 
district judge joel dubina after a presentence report is 
completed no date was set immediately 
after walkers embezzlement scheme was spelled out in hud audits 
and agency documents last year wilson initially declined to say if 
any charges against walker were being considered later it was 
disclosed that walker had arranged a deal with prosecutors to get a 
reduced prosecution in return for undercover work that led to the 
indictment of freddie hyatt on cocaine charges 
hyatt a former auburn university football star and racehorse 
trainer was convicted last september on three cocaine distribution 
counts and was sentenced to four years and three months in federal 
prison his defense attorney contended that walker framed hyatt in 
a series of calls seeking to buy cocaine 
assistant us attorney charles niven who prosecuted hyatt at 
the trial in opelika defended the plea agreement made with walker 
saying that to catch a drug dealer you use people who are 
involved in criminal activities you dont sell drugs to preachers 
or sunday school teachers 
it was brought out at the trial that walker would be allowed to 
plead guilty to the two counts 
walker used a banks wire transfer forms to embezzle the hud 
money during a period of more than two years before hud discovered 
the scheme in 1987 by the time hud officials sought to get the 
money walker had depleted the bank account 
walker acknowledged from the witness stand at the hyatt trial 
that he had used the money to buy sports cars and entertain women 
walker pleaded guilty to one count of embezzling 2073499 in 
hud funds and a second count of failing to pay federal taxes on 
711821 for the 1986 tax year 
