<TEXT>
nelson mandelas release may 
lead to talks between blacks and whites on south africas future 
but many business leaders doubt his economic theories would make 
for sound management of the continents strongest economy 
mandela the african national congress leader released feb 11 
after 27 years in prison favors state control of the countrys 
gold mines banks and monopoly industries to help redistribute the 
wealth that is disproportionately controlled by whites 
many economists and business executives say attempts to 
nationalize south africas economy will result in the stagnation 
that has plagued eastern europe and africas socialistoriented 
economies 
the anc remains locked in the past its economics 35 years 
out of date said business day a financial daily opposed to 
apartheid 
raymond parsons head of the south african chamber of business 
says if south africa is to survive in the modern global economy 
and if we are to serve the total population best we are going to 
have to expand the private enterprise ethic 
mandela and most other senior anc leaders are in their 60s or 
70s and were imprisoned or fled into exile in the early 1960s when 
scientific socialism was the favored economic system among 
africas newly independent states 
such systems have failed miserably no more than five black 
african nations have per capita incomes in excess of 1000 a year 
and none of those are socialist oriented 
yet the anc contends some degree of socialism is needed to help 
reduce the enormous gap between white wealth and black poverty 
the nationalization of mines is a fundamental policy of the 
anc mandela said after his release i believe the anc is quite 
correct in this attitude 
such talk sent the johannesburg stock exchange falling mandela 
has since sought to reassure white businessmen by saying the anc 
would consult business leaders before making any major economic 
changes and would expect both sides to compromise 
the anc is the main black group fighting the whiteminority 
government and most observers believe it would win elections if 
blacks were allowed to vote 
the organization was legalized feb 2 and plans to send a 
delegation from its headquarters in zambia to meet president fw 
de klerk and try to clear the way for talks on a new constitution 
that will include the countrys 28 million blacks 
south africa is the worlds largest gold producer and a handful 
of mining conglomerates dominate the economy 
many blacks see apartheid and capitalism as intertwined and 
feel both need to be eradicated many antiapartheid groups 
including the largest black labor federation the congress of south 
african trade unions are avowedly socialist 
south africa seems to be one of the last places on earth where 
the display of the hammer and sickle at public rallies still evokes 
cheers herman nickel a former us ambassador to south africa 
wrote recently in the wall street journal 
per capita income for south african blacks is about 1000 a 
year but whites make at least five times more on average 
economic opportunity was virtually nonexistent for blacks until 
recent years whites controlled private companies and dominated 
managerial posts in the large staterun industries such as steel 
transport and energy 
the government recently has begun to sell off huge state 
operations saying they will be more efficient as private 
companies but some blacks including mandela argue the moves are 
designed to keep wealth in white hands now that there is talk about 
the possibility of a black government 
blacks are now making some economic progress their incomes are 
rising faster than those of whites and blackrun businesses range 
from large construction firms to taxi fleets 
sam motsuenyane president of the black national african chamber 
of commerce has earned the respect of many antiapartheid leaders 
with his calls for black empowerment through economic success 
black enterprise magazine which features examples of thriving 
blackowned businesses and offers advice to aspiring entrepreneurs 
has done well since its launch several years ago 
the antiapartheid city press the countrys largest 
blackoriented newspaper said in a recent editorial that anc 
leaders have to seriously review their stand on nationalization 
while we agree there has to be some form of redistribution of 
wealth beacuse the majority of the people in this country were 
disadvantaged by the system of apartheid we tend to agree with 
motsuenyanes assertion about black economic empowerment the 
newspaper said 
</TEXT>
