<TEXT>
economic sanctions have 
retarded growth costing jobs and affecting social programs but 
whether they have pushed the government to political reform is a 
matter of argument 
we believe sanctions have been very helpful nelson mandela 
said after president fw de klerk freed the african national 
congress leader from a life prison term feb 11 
mandela also credited mass struggles inside south africa and 
changes in the thinking of government leaders for his release and 
the legalization of the anc and other organizations 
government officials and white businessmen acknowledge the 
economy has been affected by withdrawal of investments trade 
embargoes and punitive loan terms but say political changes are 
being made simply because its the right thing to do 
finance minister barend du plessis stands by the government line 
that sanctions did not influence reform although they cost the 
country wealth and jobs he said this week the reforms de klerk has 
made may ease the sanctions 
that already has happened in britains case on wednesday prime 
minister margaret thatcher lifted a ban on investments and urged 
the european economic community to end other punishments as an 
encouragement to de klerk 
kent durr the south african trade minister said the british 
action would encourage negotiations on an end to apartheid 
when de klerk returned from meetings with mrs thatcher and 
other european leaders in june he said international pressure and 
economic sanctions may ease as long as it is visible that were 
really working to end apartheid and white domination of the 
government 
he has since ended segregation of beaches allowed huge 
antigovernment demonstrations legalized 60 organizations freed 
some political prisoners suspended all executions and partially 
lifted the state of emergency 
de klerk never said he was caving in to foreign pressure as 
rightwing opponents claim but he has clearly linked south 
africas internal economic and political problems with its 
international image 
the time has come for south africa to restore its pride and to 
lift itself out of the doldrums of growing international isolation 
economic decline and increasing polarization he said at his 
inauguration in september 
we are going to open the door to prosperity and economic 
growth by breaking out of the international stranglehold which 
for political reasons has been applied to our growth potential 
nico czypionka chief economist of the standard bank said 
sanctions did certainly undercut economic growth but i dont 
think that was the factor that triggered the political changes 
taking place 
he said the black population boom and urbanization of hundreds 
of thousands of rural blacks probably contributed to the 
goverments movement toward reform 
financial experts agree the most damaging sanctions were those 
by lenders in 1985 creditor banks decided not to renew loans and 
to impose strict credit policies 
economists at the trust bank estimate south africa would have 
had 14 billion more in loans and investment in the past five years 
and 4 billion more in export earnings had it not been for 
sanctions and political turmoil 
sanctions also forced businesses to increase efficiency showed 
consumers they could do without many imported luxuries and caused 
the government to change its financial policy 
most of the nearly 200 foreign companies that left south africa 
sold their local operations to domestic owners for low prices to be 
paid over long terms few jobs were lost but many social 
educational housing and training programs begun by foreigners were 
dropped 
</TEXT>
