<TEXT>
a sculptor told lawmakers he would never 
have entered a competition to design a major state statue if he 
knew they were going put it on the ground instead of on top of the 
statehouse dome 
the proposed 20foot statue named ad astra from the states 
motto ad astra per aspera or to the stars through 
difficulty was designed by richard bergen of salina it depicts 
a male kansa indian pointing a bow and arrow toward the sky 
after years of debate about a plan to put a statue of ceres the 
goddess of agriculture and fertility atop the capitol dome the 
1984 legislature authorized the kansas arts commission to conduct a 
competition and choose an alternative statue 
bergens design was named the winner in 1988 and he was awarded 
a 1500 prize plus the promise of a contract to produce the 
fullsized work for 50000 he told the house economic development 
committee on tuesday he could have it done in one year 
however the project ran into a major problem an assessment of 
the domes structural condition produced an estimate that it could 
cost as much as 400000 to shore it up so it could hold the 
twoton statue 
the 1989 legislature declined to appropriate the money 
a bill introduced this year would place ad astra on a pedestal 
base on the statehouse grounds rather than on the dome at a cost 
of only 25000 
bergen strenuously objected 
i designed this originally to go up on the dome he told 
lawmakers tuesday i dont want it on the ground if they had 
said they wanted it on the ground i wouldnt have been in the 
competition 
thats not the way kansans work we complete our tasks he 
said if i have to go out and raise the money to put it up there 
ill do it 
bergen argued the dome is sound enough to hold his statue if the 
state would just perform normal maintenance and spend a nominal 
amount to shore it up 
he also said the 400000 estimated cost is inflated because it 
contains 100000 in contingency fees in case costs wind up higher 
than expected he said he can get a helicopter on loan to do hoist 
work eliminating a 78000 expense 
i think we ought to go ahead and put the thing up there he 
told the committee 
lucinda foster chairwoman of the arts commission said the 
statue is shaped to be viewed from 300 feet away and putting it on 
the ground would detract from its esthetic value 
this proposal unfortunately raises more problems than it 
solves unless it is a temporary plan mrs foster said 
</TEXT>
