colder weather in the great plains winter 
wheat area after two months of relatively balmy temperatures is 
reminding farmers that it is still february after all 
winter returned to the northern and central plains as arctic 
air plunged south and reversed the warm spell of the last two 
months the governments joint agricultural weather facility said 
wednesday 
rain benefited winter wheat in portions of the central and 
southern great plains in the week of feb 1117 the report 
said although additional moisture was needed in kansas 
the facility is operated by the departments of agriculture and 
commerce the weekly reports cover weather and crop conditions but 
do not include crop production forecasts 
also the period covered did not include more recent 
precipitation in the plains area including up to a foot of snow in 
the oklahoma panhandle and parts of western kansas 
in a related report the usda said wheat inventories may drop to 
443 million bushels by the beginning of the next marketing year on 
june 1 the lowest in 15 years and down from 702 million bushels a 
year ago 
however increases in planted area and a return to normal 
yields in 1990 will likely allow modest stock rebuilding if use is 
similar to the previous two years the departments economic 
research service said 
the us area planted to winter wheat last fall is up 3 percent 
even though an additional 19 million acres of wheat base were 
