<TEXT>
scientists conducting genetic experiments with 
ordinary pond scum say it may one day be an automatic dispenser of 
fertilizer in rice fields 
but the scientists who work for the agricultural research 
service in the agriculture department said wednesday it may be 
another 15 years before rice growers are able to use the pond scum 
or bluegreen algae as a fertilizer source 
if the procedure can be developed the natural fertilizer 
dispensed by the special algae could have a significant effect on 
rice production around the world including many third world 
countries that rely on the crop as a food staple 
stephen albrecht a plant physiologist at the agencys 
laboratory in gainesville fla said greenhouse tests with the 
altered algae boosted rice production eightfold however he said 
it didnt do well in the field probably because the algae had not 
been adapted to field conditions 
normally pond algae produces just enough nutrientrich ammonia 
from nitrogen in the atmosphere to take care of its own needs the 
genetically engineered strains keep producing as long as nearby 
plants need the nutrients 
when rice plants stop taking in ammonia the algae stops 
production before excess amounts spill over into the environment 
albrecht said the onandoff fertilizing system could mean less 
groundwater contamination tests showed that while rice with algae 
at its roots had some ammonia there was none in the environment 
if the algae can be adapted to rice fields albrecht said 
growers could grow algae alongside rice fields and flood it into 
the rice areas at irrigation time he said it would be cheaper and 
require less work than with commercial fertilizers 
