<TEXT>
attempts to reform deposit insurance could do 
more harm than good to the nations financial system says a top 
regulator who warns that many proposals circulating would cause 
negative side effects 
injecting more market discipline into the banking system 
although desirable would involve tradeoffs that include greater 
financial instability and less protection for consumers said l 
william seidman chairman of the federal deposit insurance corp 
this is a dangerous subject he said wednesday dont grab 
for easy quick solutions or youre liable to blow yourself out of 
the water 
the house banking committee hearing which also featured general 
accounting office head charles a bowsher opened what promises to 
be the most explosive financial industry issue before congress in 
the next few years 
many private analysts believe deposit insurance helped encourage 
the risky behavior that led to mammoth sampl losses depositors have 
little or no reason to care whether they were placing their money 
in a sound institution they argue 
congress considered the question too hot to handle in last 
years sampl bill and ordered the treasury department and bowshers 
agency congress auditing and investigative arm to study the 
mattter and make recommendations by next february 
bowsher gave little hint of the gaos ultimate stance but urged 
legislators not to lose sight of the benefits of the system 
deposit insurance deserves much of the credit for the fact 
that there was no serious loss of confidence in the banking 
system during the 1970s and 1980s when the nation experienced 
oil shocks inflation the worst recession since the great 
depression and a stock market crash he said 
on other matters seidman 
said the fdic was investigating whether it had the authority to 
curb socalled golden parachute contracts that provide bank and 
sampl executives with lucrative severance benefits if their 
institution fails perversely sometimes executives benefit more 
from an institutions failure than its success he said 
issued a new more pessimistic assessment of the commercial bank 
insurance funds condition the fund which lost 4 billion in 1988 
and declined again in 1989 likely will about break even in 
1990 he said ending the year around 14 billion 
the reason is weve developed some real problems in real 
estate in the northeast and down the east coast and we dont know 
how much if anything thats going to cost us he said 
he said at this time the agency does not expect any major 
bank failures among institutions currently reporting increased 
losses 
both bowsher and seidman conceded the failure of hundreds of 
banks and sampls in recent years make it clear the governments 
exposure to loss must be limited 
however seidman warned depositors must experience real 
losses to develop real market discipline he added no one 
really knows what would happen if a large bank were allowed to 
default on deposit obligations 
so far regulators have been unwilling to risk the chance that a 
failure of a big bank would bring down the entire financial system 
he said one of the most common reform proposals reducing the 
100000 insurance limit would probably be ineffective most 
depositors would simply divide their money into smaller chunks and 
spread it among more institutions 
a rule limiting depositors to just one insured account among all 
banks and sampls would be difficult to administer he said 
nevertheless reps henry b gonzalez dtexas the chairman of 
the committee said congress must consider reducing the 100000 
deposit insurance limit arguing it is too broad and has gotten 
away from its original purpose protection of the small 
depositor but he said legislation was unlikely until next year 
after completion of the gao and treasury studies 
both gonzalez and rep chalmers wylie of ohio the panels 
senior republican said expansion of bank investment powers long 
sought by the industry will not be considered separately from 
deposit insurance reform 
