<TEXT>
the only leper colony in the continental 
united states will be converted to a health care center for elderly 
and crippled federal prisoners officials said 
us rep clyde holloway rla said wednesday that the 
agreement between the bureau of prisons and the public health 
service should be signed early next week 
the 130 leprosy patients who live at the gillis w long hansens 
disease center in carville about 70 miles west of new orleans would 
be allowed to remain holloway said 
its a winwin situation holloway said 
the 340acre facility in an isolated curve of river will be 
able to hold about 1000 prisoners he said 
it was the last us public health service hospital in the 
country the federal research project on leprosy now known as 
hansens disease will be moved from the center 20 miles up the 
mississippi river to baton rouge 
the colony opened in 1894 on an old plantation the federal 
government took control in 1921 and as many as 500 residents lived 
there during the 1930s 
the center has treated nearly 3000 patients and survived the 
1984 reagan administration budget cuts when seven other public 
health service hospitals closed 
all major advances in leprosy treatment drugs 
armadillorelated discoveries and two generations of vaccines with 
limited effectiveness came from carvilles researchers said 
center director john duffy 
leprosy a bacterial infection causes nerve damage that can 
result in loss of muscle control crippling of the hands and feet 
and blindness most cases can be treated before complications set 
in and treatment makes the disease noncontagious 
two hundred to 300 new cases are diagnosed every year with an 
estimated 10000 us victims and 20 million worldwide 
