<TEXT>
fifteen cities around the country will 
share 27 million for programs to deter alcohol and drug abuse the 
robert wood johnson foundation announced 
the amount to be spent over five years is the largest sum from 
a single private source to combat substance abuse 
urban cities and rural communities were selected including an 
area of northwestern new mexico that covers portions of the navajo 
and zuni reservations 
foundation president dr leighton e cluff said wednesday that 
the program is aimed at developing successful models that can be 
copied elsewhere 
each of the 15 communities selected from 331 applicants must 
develop a program to reduce alcohol and illegal drug abuse among 
residents 
planning would be done in each city by a coalition of educators 
health officials law enforcement authorities and representatives 
of labor business religious organizations and government agencies 
each municipality will receive 100000 a year for at least two 
years for planning and will be encouraged to seek additional 
funding from outside sources eight of the 15 will then be chosen 
to receive 3 million each to continue developing their models 
the cities include newark washington dc new haven conn 
worcester mass west charlotte nc san antonio little rock 
ark milwaukee kansas city mo columbia sc and the 
california cities of vallejo east oakland san jose and santa 
barbara 
the robert wood johnson foundation describes itself as the 
nations largest private health care philanthrophy with 2 billion 
in assets and 100 million annually in grants it is named for the 
late son of one of the founders of the johnson amp johnson health 
care products company 
