the senate judiciary committee today approved 
the nomination of clarence thomas the conservative chairman of the 
equal employment opportunity commission to be a federal appeals 
court judge 
the nomination was approved 121 with sen howard m metzenbaum 
dohio voting against it it now goes to the full senate 
some civil rights forces had opposed the nomination because of 
thomas opposition to affirmative action programs and his other 
conservative views but the national association for the 
advancement of colored people announced two weeks ago that it would 
not stand in the way of confirmation 
thomas one of the most visible blacks in the republican 
administrations of former president reagan and president george 
bush was nominated to the us circuit court of appeals in the 
district of columbia 
at his confirmation hearing last week thomas said state and 
local agencies were primarily to blame for more than 900 cases of 
alleged job discrimination lapsing without action 
critics from womens and senior citizens groups said the number 
of lapsed cases actually ran into the thousands metzenbaum said 
the responsibility rested with the commission itself 
i was flabbergasted that he did not know that state agencies 
are under contract to process state age discrimination claims 
metzenbaum said 
sen edward m kennedy dmass said that he and thomas 
disagree about certain aspects of civil rights policy and that 
he is concerned about the commissions failure to ensure that age 
discrimination claims were investigated within the statute of 
limitations 
but kennedy said a court of appeals judge neither makes 
policy nor presides over an administrative agency he added that 
thomas has the ability to serve with distinction on the court of 
appeals and i support his confirmation 
if confirmed thomas would take the place of robert bork on the 
appeals court because it is located in the nations capital it 
frequently is called on to decide major governmental cases and it 
has often been a springboard to the us supreme court 
bork resigned after his nomination to the supreme court was 
rejected by the senate in the most bitter judicial fight of recent 
years 
thomas born in poverty in rural georgia is a graduate of yale 
law school he worked for sen john c danforth rmo both in 
danforths senate office and when he was missouri attorney general 
thomas was recommended to the panel at his confirmation hearing 
by danforth and by sens sam nunn dga and charles robb dva 
