<TEXT>
washington ap the energy department today awarded a 1 
billion engineering and construction contract for a a highpowered 
atom smasher to a team led by a new york firm according to members 
of congress 
the contract was awarded to a consortium of three companies led 
by parsons brinckerhoff quade and douglas inc of new york city 
also on the team are crss inc of houston and morrison knudsen 
corp of boise idaho officials said 
officials say the award is the largest single contract involved 
in building the superconducting super collider a 53mile 
underground ring where scientists would test theories about the 
building blocks of the universe by smashing atomic particles at 
high speeds 
the team was chosen from three finalists selected in december 
out of a field of 14 to compete for the contract to build the atom 
smasher at a site south of dallas in ellis county 
terms of the contract must still be negotiated officials said 
rep joe barton rennis whose district includes the site for 
the facility said the contract is a sign the project is moving 
forward despite an anticipated billiondollar increase in cost and 
questions about the technology 
larry neal a spokesman for sen phil gramm rtexas parsons 
brinckerhoff is the lead contractor and would do the architectural 
and engineering contracting work with knudsen and crss doing the 
construction work 
congress has appropriated 225 million for the collider 
including 160 million for construction work during this fiscal 
year president bush is seeking an additional 318 million for the 
fiscal year that begins oct 1 
because of design changes the cost of the project is expected 
to increase from 59 billion to at least 7 billion 
the collider would be the worlds largest scientific instrument 
</TEXT>
