<TEXT>
aflcio leaders today urged unions to 
renew support for striking machinists at eastern airlines and 
declared that the nearly yearlong strike remains as solid as 
ever 
leaders of the 141 millionmember federation set to adjourn 
their winter meeting later in the day issued a statement saying 
the 8500 machinists had inspired workers nationwide by being on 
the front lines of labors battle against corporate greed and 
intransigence 
machinists who walked out last march have faced stiff odds with 
a bush administration that doesnt care about the survival of 
eastern airlines and has sided with management in the matter the 
federation said 
eastern was the only major point of contention when union 
leaders met with labor secretary elizabeth dole earlier in the week 
aflcio president lane kirkland has conceded that so far the 
strike has failed but said easterns parent texas air corp has 
not won either 
labor leaders also acknowledged they still lack enough votes in 
congress to override president bushs veto of legislation that 
would create a commission to settle the dispute 
the eastern situation has been a sore spot for labor leaders 
this week who otherwise have been buoyed by signs that organized 
labor may be recovering from a bleak decade 
the machinists strike marks a strong contrast to labors recent 
successes by pittston coal miners and nynex telephone workers in 
the northeast 
just today the federations executive council received a report 
by the roper organization showing that more americans instinctively 
side with unions than with companies in labor disputes 
weve been tempered i think by a period of fire and in the 
net result its strengthened us kirkland said 
the pollsters found in their most recent tracking surveys that 
33 percent instinctively side with the union while 25 percent favor 
the company when they first hear of a strike and before they know 
any of the details 
that was the highest level of support for unions and the lowest 
for companies recorded by the company since it posed the question 
to sample groups 12 years ago 
roper reports are sponsored by the aflcio and 40 other 
organizations including government agencies the company conducts 
facetoface interviews with new groups of 2000 adults every five 
weeks 
union leaders were cheered by the results given the decline in 
stature organized labor suffered in the 1980s with losses in 
membership 
also serving as a rallying point for labor leaders this week was 
the success of the appalachian coal strike pittston miners who 
won on key bargaining points ended their bitter 10month strike 
tuesday by ratifying a new contract 
united mine workers president richard trumka who last year 
brought his union back into the aflcio and others said the public 
looks more favorably on unions because unions have avoided 
focusing so narrowly on shop floor issues 
there are 38 million americans without health care whats the 
only group thats really fighting for health care thats organized 
labor trumka said 
the roper report showed that in 1981 60 percent of americans 
thought unreasonable demands by labor unions made the cost of 
living go up unneccesarily that number has now dropped to 40 
percent the survey showed 
noting the decline of bluecollar jobs in the manufacturing 
area the report said the image of unions had gained in the eyes of 
professional and white collar workers groups that formerly were 
