<TEXT>
an explosion ripped through a 
usflagged petroleum tanker in the persian gulf today leaving 
two americans missing and setting off fires that forced the rest of 
the crew to abandon ship the navy said 
a us frigate patrolling nearby rescued 23 crew members from 
the sea and some were injured said capt ron wildermuth chief 
spokesman for the navys central command in florida two of the 
injured were airlifted to a hospital in dubai 
one of the rescued men said all 25 crewmen on the surf city a 
kuwaiti tanker flying the us flag were americans but this was 
not immediately confirmed 
the cause of the explosion was not known initial reports 
indicated it was an accident said wildermuth 
in washington pentagon spokesman bob hall said there were 
indications the explosion was internal he did not elaborate 
crewman wayne cohen said the blast occurred about 1100 am 
while crew members were working on a cargo tank on the ship which 
was loaded with millions of gallons of highly volatile products 
it was a huge explosion the whole ship just blew up said 
cohen 27 of boston who was cut by glass and airlifted to a 
hospital in dubai 
the glass in the bridge blew out there was some panic and we 
all made our way to the lifeboat he said cohen said he saw 
nothing but fire and smoke as he looked back at the tanker from 
the lifeboat 
the 81283ton surf city carried 178 million gallons of naphtha 
and 89 million gallons of gasoil industry sources said us navy 
units and the united arab emirates coast guard put out four blazes 
but a fifth continued to burn more than six hours after the blast 
and ships nearby moved away for fear of another explosion 
the ship is halfsunk now and it might sink totally said a 
member of the dubai coast guard 
shipping sources said on condition of anonymity the tanker had 
been loaded in kuwait and was on its way out of the gulf the ship 
was off the coast of the united arab emirates near the iranian 
island of abu musa when the explosion occurred 
abu musa was a stronghold of iranian revolutionary guards and 
was used as a base to attack ships at the height of the iraniraq 
war there have been no attacks on shipping in the gulf since iran 
and iraq signed a ceasefire agreement in august 1988 
wildermuth said the uss simpson was 15 miles away from the surf 
city at the time of the accident and rushed to its aid the uss 
dewey a missile destroyer was also in the vicinity and joined the 
rescue operation along with united arab emirates vessels he said 
the shipping sources said the simpson one of about 10 us navy 
ships in the gulf was escorting the surf city at the time of the 
accident 
the navy said direct escorts of kuwaiti tankers by american 
warships stopped after the ceasefire and that us warships now 
monitor americanflagged ships in the gulf from a distance 
kuwait put 11 of its tankers under the us flag in 1987 to 
receive us navy protection from iran which was concentrating 
attacks on kuwaitiflagged vessels in retaliation for kuwaiti aid 
to iraq 
kuwait last year reached agreement with the united states to 
revert six of the 11 tankers to kuwaiti registry surf city was one 
of the five remaining usflagged tankers expected to revert to 
the kuwaiti flag this month 
us maritime law requires that all crew members of us flagged 
ships be us citizens but an exception was made at the time of 
the reflagging in 1987 
cohen said all the crew of the surf city were americans he 
identified another crewmen airlifted to the same dubai hospital as 
earl washington a boatswain no other details on the injured were 
immediately available 
the central command in florida which oversees the navy force in 
the gulf said it was told at least one of the ships crewmen was 
britishcanadian 
