<TEXT>
civil rights veterans who for decades have 
carried the rev martin luther kings banner of nonviolence are 
uneasy over nelson mandelas refusal to renounce violence but are 
reluctant to criticize the south african 
for colleagues and followers of king the release of mandela 
this month after 27 years in prison has posed something of a moral 
dilemma 
as longtime opponents of apartheid they are joyful over 
mandelas freedom but the refusal by mandela and the african 
national congress to rule out the use of arms is at odds with the 
nonviolent philosophy espoused by king 
followers of king however say they believe the slain civil 
rights leader if alive today would not condemn mandela for his 
position 
we still subscribe to nonviolence but we dont believe we 
have a right to dictate to other people how to achieve their 
liberation said the rev joseph lowery president of the 
kingfounded southern christian leadership conference 
while i personally choose other tactics i grant them the 
right to choose how to get the heels off of their necks 
david j garrow a pulitzer prizewinning biographer of king 
said thursday that supporting mandela is less of a problem for 
kings followers than it would have been for king himself 
theres no getting around the fact that kings belief in 
nonviolence was so total and central that he could not have 
endorsed the tactical position of the anc said garrow an 
associate professor of political science at city college of new 
york 
but i think the totality of kings commitment to nonviolence 
was relatively unusual even within the southern christian 
leadership conference he said i dont necessarily think 
theres any contradiction or alteration involved for a lot of 
people to say they happily endorse mandela and the anc 
those who worked closely with king said they would prefer using 
the principles of nonviolence preached by king to overcome 
apartheid but they said they can understand because of the 
violence suffered by blacks in south africa why mandela feels he 
cannot rule out violence in selfdefense 
we had this argument in the early stages of the civil rights 
movement said kings widow coretta scott king we worked with 
people who told martin if they hit me ill hit back 
he told them if they were going to join the movement 
theyd have to be nonviolent mrs king said in an interview 
last week many people in the marches were not nonviolent but 
became nonviolent as time went on 
mrs king said her husband didnt condemn those who disagreed 
with him but tried through his own actions to demonstrate the 
effectiveness of nonviolence 
lowery said king unequivocally opposed violence but still was 
supportive of the african national congress before his 
assassination in 1968 the associations violence posed him a 
moral problem and a theological problem lowery said but i 
dont know that he ever condemned the anc 
king frequently spoke out against south africas racial 
segregation he advocated worldwide economic sanctions against 
south africa to destroy apartheid 
in a 1964 speech on south africa however king said we can 
understand how in that situation people felt so desperate that they 
turned to other methods such as sabotage 
lowery stressed that mandela has endorsed only defensive 
violence not aggressive force 
the rev hosea williams a former atlanta city councilman who 
was kings field general in the peak days of the civil rights 
movement said he disagrees with the use of violence in south 
africa but would not withdraw his support for the antiapartheid 
effort 
mandela is advocating protective violence which is much 
different from dr kings total nonviolence advocacy williams 
said we never found anything more effective than nonviolence 
williams said the refusal of blacks to resort to violence even 
after the beatings suffered by demonstrators in alabama in 1965 
drew sympathy from the public and provided support to force federal 
civil rights legislation 
the use of violence by the anc williams suggested could 
jeopardize such popular support for the antiapartheid movement 
id plead with mr mandela to give up on any sort of violence 
and resort totally to nonviolence but i certainly could not 
withdraw my support for the black struggle in south africa 
williams said 
