<TEXT>
a coast guard investigator said today 
he cannot explain why the exxon valdez disappeared from radar and 
then reappeared after is had run aground on bligh reef 
lt cmdr thomas falkenstein confirmed that the coast guard had 
responsibility for monitoring the tanker during its transit into 
prince william sound but also confirmed that the ship was not 
visible on radar some time before its disastrous accident 
coast guard monitors have testified that the ship was visible on 
the radar after its skipper joseph hazelwood radioed that it was 
aground 
if you are asking why it was off radar and secondarily was on 
radar i dont know falkenstein said under questioning by 
hazelwood attorney michael chalos 
the 43yearold hazelwood of huntington ny is charged with 
seconddegree criminal mischief a felony and three misdemeanors 
reckless endangerment operating a vessel while intoxicated and 
negligent discharge of oil 
the officer who was one of the first on board the ship after it 
ran aground said he smelled alcohol on hazelwoods breath and 
immediatetly sent word to shore that someone should be sent to test 
the captains blood alcohol level 
he also testified that federal regulations followed by the coast 
guard required that a vessel going through the valdez narrows into 
prince william sound must be under the direction and control of 
an officer who has been certified as specially trained for that 
area 
hazelwood was the only officer on board with such a 
certification when the accident occurred and he was not on the 
ships bridge 
in testimony wednesday an exxon official said that hazelwood 
indicated the disaster was his fault and he was to blame for the 
nations worst oil spill 
paul myers of danville calif told jurors hazelwood appeared 
to be taking responsiblity as captain of the ship but he was 
prevented from answering a question about whether hazelwood also 
was accepting criminal blame 
hazelwood told him the ship pride of the exxon fleet was 
damaged but safe and said there was oil in the waters of prince 
william sound myers recalled 
he indicated this had happened and it was his fault he was to 
blame myers said he had just gone down to do some paperwork 
when this happened and he should have been on the bridge 
the tanker leaked nearly 11 million gallons of alaska crude oil 
into prince william sound the disaster killed countless birds 
fish and wildlife and blackened hundreds of miles of rocky shore 
nearly a year later it still is being cleaned up 
exxon officials announced wednesday that the company will resume 
its cleanup of the remaining oil may 1 exxon suspended its cleanup 
in september because of the onset of severe winter weather but had 
declined to set a date for further work 
the company found serious problems along about 10 of the 90 
miles of shoreline its crews surveyed said hann jahns an exxon 
scientist 
earlier in the trial hazelwood was quoted as telling a coast 
guard investigator who asked what the ships problem was i think 
youre looking at it a witness said the anguished skipper was 
referring to himself 
another exxon tanker captain on wednesday told jurors for the 
first time that the giant oil company is concerned about the 
outcome of hazelwoods trial michael stalzer said exxon has paid 
for his lawyer and for legal representation of all crew members who 
are testifying in the trial 
i believe exxon does have an interest in the outcome of this 
case he said 
exxon is the defendant in more than 150 civil lawsuits resulting 
from the oil spill but hazelwood is the only defendant charged 
criminally 
stalzer who preceded hazelwood as commander of the exxon valdez 
and replaced him after the accident indicated that hazelood 
violated several sections of a company operating manual in his 
command of the illfated ship 
stalzer said he would not have left the ships bridge during a 
potentially hazardous passage around ice in prince william sound 
hazelwood left the ship in control of the third mate 10 minutes 
before it grounded 
but he said none of the violations was against the law and that 
the exxon bridge manual was merely a guideline and statement of 
company policies on how to run a tanker 
the prosecution seeks to prove that hazelwoods actions were 
reckless and endangered the property and lives of others 
stalzer described the exxon valdez as the newest and probably 
most technically advanced of the tankers in exxons approximately 
30ship fleet 
starting may 1 exxon will resume its cleanup of oil remaining 
in prince william sound and the gulf of alaska from the nations 
largest oil spill company officials said wednesday 
exxon suspended its cleanup in september because of the onset of 
severe winter weather but had declined to set a date for further 
work 
