<TEXT>
between 18 million and 23 million east 
germans will resettle in west germany this decade a study said 
thursday but it did not specifically address how the rush toward 
reunification would affect the trend 
the number of resettlers will depend in large part on the pace 
of political and economic reforms in what is now east germany 
according to the respected diw research institute of west berlin 
while the comprehensive study did not specifically address the 
most recent steps toward unification east germanys economic 
problems are so enormous that the political joining of the two 
countries is unlikely to slow the migration 
the prospects of massive unemployment in what is now east 
germany once freemarket reforms take hold and a higher standard of 
living in the west are likely to keep fueling the exodus 
full integration of the two countries could take several years 
already this year about 100000 east germans reached the west 
severely straining local governments ability to house and provide 
for them more than 340000 east germans made the same trek last 
year 
they have already contributed to a massive housing shortage in 
one of europes most populous countries while many west germans 
have called for curbs on the influx 
many fear that even an expected unification will do little to 
halt the westward flow diw officially called the deutsches 
institut fuer wirtschaftsforschung confirmed some of those fears 
the economics research institute said if comprehensive reforms 
are put into motion quickly and there is hope of creating more 
prosperity the number of people leaving what is now east germany 
will be 18 million by the end of the century 
diw said that situation would lead to an average exodus of 
230000 people a year through 1995 
diw also projected a situation in which the east germans 
perceive the reform process is being delayed in that case 
said the study 23 million people from east germany will resettle 
in the west in the 1990s 
west german businesses already are entering into joint ventures 
in east germany with the agreements calling for massive layoffs to 
make businesses more efficient that and other economic pressures 
are likely to create even further difficulties and drive more 
people out 
many of those leaving are young skilled workers whose talents 
are desperately needed for east germanys faltering economy 
many other problems are also afflicting east germany including 
crumbling housing and staggering pollution problems many of these 
problems will take years to resolve 
east germans arent the only ones heading to the riches of west 
germany an estimated 377000 ethnic germans from other parts of 
eastern europe arrived last year and tens of thousands are 
expected this year 
the diw study said that 13 million ethnic germans would 
resettle in west germany by the end of the decade if reforms in the 
rest of eastern europe proceed at a brisk pace the number would be 
16 million in the event the changes slow down 
west germany has about 624 million people while the population 
of east germany is a little more than 16 million 
