<TEXT>
six nationwide telemarketing firms all based 
in arlington texas have been charged with fraudulent practices 
involving the sale of home water treatment products the government 
said thursday 
investigators raided the telephone boiler rooms of the 
companies a day earlier seized their records and obtained 
temporary court orders freezing their assets and barring them from 
future misrepresentations the federal trade commission said 
the move was the seventh major enforcement action by the ftc 
since 1987 against firms that allegedly have preyed upon consumers 
fears about the safety of their drinking water by marketing 
products under false or misleading claims 
the texas operation was coordinated with the justice department 
the us postal inspection service and the texas attorney generals 
office said barry j cutler director of the ftcs bureau of 
consumer protection 
cutler said the ftc had filed two civil complaints in us 
district court in fort worth seeking refunds to the defendants 
customers and permanent injunctions against fraudulent practices in 
the future 
one complaint was lodged against five firms gtp marketing inc 
telstar marketing network inc hs marketing inc unitel 
marketing consultants inc and mbc group inc all located at the 
same watson road address in arlington three individuals todd 
arnold stephen gregg echols and pat arnold also were named in 
that complaint 
a reporters call to those individuals at the number listed for 
unitel was not immediately returned three of the companies were 
not publicly listed the telephone listed at the fourth hs 
marketing was not answered 
the second complaint was aimed at c amp l industries inc and 
its two officers ramon haas and t w bodiford both were said by 
a secretary to be out of the office and unavailable for comment on 
thursday 
ever since water quality emerged as a consumer concern a 
couple of years ago fraudulent telemarketers and others have 
aggressively promoted their products by using scare tactics 
blatantly false claims about federal endorsements of their 
products and gross exaggerations about their products ability to 
cleanse and purify water cutler said 
they offer lavish awards and prizes and moneyback guarantees 
they will say anything to make a sale he said 
in the case of c amp l which markets the atlantis water 
purification system the firm told prospective customers several 
falsehoods including claims that a bill pending in congress will 
require every home to have a water treatment device and that its 
product had been endorsed by the government and was used on the 
us space shuttle according to the ftc complaint 
cutler said c amp l also claimed that unpure water killed more 
people last year in the united states than cholesterol and nicotine 
combined and that its device marketed for 450500 could 
virtually eliminate such contaminants as lead bacteria radon gas 
acid rain pesticides and industrial runoff from up to 15000 
gallons or more of tap water 
not only will the device not do that he said but you could 
go to the hardware store and get something like it for less than 
100 
the five other firms were charged with luring in customers by 
mailing them postcards claiming they had won valuable awards such 
as a cadillac or 5000 in merchandise checks in fact the awards 
required payment of substantial additional sums of money the 
ftc complaint said and when consumers called in the firms falsely 
claimed they needed their creditcard numbers to verify their 
eligibility and then debited those accounts without 
authorization the complaint charged further that many consumers 
who did order a product such as a water treatment unit never 
received it 
cutler noted that there are many legitimate companies selling 
useful home water treatment devices and consumers who do their 
homework can get their moneys worth 
</TEXT>
