impossible to allocate the nations limited funds the chairman 
of a senate panel said thursday 
the general accounting office the investigative arm of 
congress found that the air force lacks adequate accounting 
systems for its 275 billion in weapons systems inventories and 
other assets and annual appropriations of about 90 billion 
in response to news stories on the report sen john glenn 
dohio chairman of the senate governmental affairs committee 
issued a statement criticizing the air force and urging the service 
to act quickly to rectify its accounting problems 
this audit has uncovered some significant weaknesses which 
make it all but impossible for us to allocate our limited resources 
wisely or to identify areas that are highly susceptible to waste 
and fraud glenn said 
following a threeyear audit the gao discovered that among 
other things the air force understated the cost of the b1 bomber 
by at least 71 billion in its financial statements 
the air force accounting and financial management systems can 
neither provide complete and reliable financial data nor be 
depended upon to report accurately on the resources entrusted to 
its managers the gao said 
a draft copy of the report was obtained by the associated press 
the report faulted the air forces financial systems as being 
unable to provide managers with complete and reliable information 
on either acquisition or operating costs of aircrafts and missiles 
the procurement cost for each b1 bomber is reported by the 
air force to be 150 million gao found that the cost is in fact 
about 219 million similar underestimates exist with the f15 
and f16 aircraft the agency said 
charles bowsher us comptroller general plans to testify 
before the senate panel friday on the gao report 
meanwhile at the pentagon officials released a twopage letter 
the defense departments comptroller general sent to the gao on the 
report as well as a pointbypoint response to the agencys 26 
recommendations 
the department is concerned that the report may mislead some 
readers into thinking that the air force has misstated the cost of 
its aircraft or other programs to the congress sean okeefe the 
pentagons comptroller general wrote 
he said the air force reports its costs to congress through 
several channels 
but he also said the air force understands its accounting system 
needs improvement 
the gao report titled air force does not effectively account 
for billions of dollars of resources found that the service 
reported 638 billion in supplies and spare parts eight times 
the inventories of general motors 
however the systems used to provide accountability over these 
immense inventories do not provide reliable data supporting either 
their quantities or value the gao said 
the agency also discovered that almost 630 million worth of 
satellites and about 57 million worth of engines for c20a cargo 
planes that the air force paid for and owned were not recorded in 
any air force property or accounting system 
</TEXT>
