about 2 percent because of increased cattle marketings and heavier 
weights the departments economics research service said in its 
report 
but an expanding us population and increases in net beef 
exports will more than offset the larger output the report said 
that will mean less beef available on a per capita basis 
consequently market prices of choicegrade fed steers sold on 
the omaha neb market in 1990 may average about 1 more than last 
years record of 7250 per pound the report said that would push 
retail prices up 1 percent to 3 percent 
hog prices also are going up and may average in the range of 47 
to 53 per 100 pounds in 1990 compared with a little more than 44 
last year at the major markets 
retail pork prices have risen in recent months reflecting 
higher hog prices and wider farmtoretail marketing spreads 
the report said retail pork prices for the year may increase 6 
percent to 8 percent from last year 
