the political outlook may have improved a bit 
for the north in new census population estimates 
the south and west will wrest away some seats in the house of 
representatives after the 1990 national head count but maybe not 
as many as had originally been thought 
the constitution requires seats in the house to be redistributed 
among states after each census 
the private population reference bureau analyzed a complex 
series of new census estimates on thursday and predicted that 14 
house seats will move from the northeast and midwest to the south 
and west after the census 
earlier analyses by the same group had indicated as many as 18 
seats would move 
the census estimates include four sets of possible state 
populations for 1990 each differing slightly depending on the 
amount of interstate movement by people 
one set included no movement and was discounted by the private 
analysis group 
but while reapportionment calculations based on the other three 
varied slightly the overall shift in seats was consistent 
the big winner will be california gaining six seats based on 
the new figures the previous calculations had called for 
california to gain five seats 
texas and florida will gain three seats each the new estimates 
indicate earlier calculations had shown texas adding four seats 
and florida three 
arizona and georgia which had previously been expected to gain 
two seats apiece are now expected to add one the new study said 
virginia also will gain one as had been expected north 
carolina would add one seat under two of the estimates but would 
remain unchanged under the third 
on the losing side new york is still expected to lose three 
seats pennsylvania which had been expected to drop three now 
appears likely to lose just two ohio illinois and michigan will 
drop two each the same as previously expected 
also unchanged are losses of one seat each by west virginia 
iowa kansas and massachusetts 
