<TEXT>
the bush administration thursday said it 
opposed a house bill that would increase taxes on employers to 
protect the jobless from a sudden cut in unemployment benefits in a 
severe recession 
the national governors association said it also objected to the 
bill which would raise the federal unemployment insurance taxable 
wage base from 7000 to 10000 
the bill by reps thomas downey dny donald pease dohio 
and sander levin dmich is aimed at averting a repeat of the 
198182 recession when cashstarved states cut benefits and 
restricted eligibility as their jobless rates soared above 10 
percent 
we see no programatic justification for such an increase 
deputy assistant labor secretary carolyn golding told the house 
ways and means subcommittee on human resources which is chaired by 
downey 
ms golding said the unemployment trust funds now have state and 
federal reserves totaling 45 billion she said one state 
michigan still owes 800 million from the 14 billion borrowed by 
26 states in 198284 to meet benefit payments 
some states remain in positions that could require borrowing 
if such a downturn occurred ms golding said but there has 
been significant overall improvement in the solvency of the trust 
funds 
despite the improvement congressional auditors in the general 
accounting office said thursday the reserves still appear to be 
inadequate to handle a severe recession 
at the end of 1989 only six states had enough reserves to 
maintain benefits in a severe recession for 18 months the target 
recommended in the past by the labor department and most state 
employment security administrators the gao said 
and the overall system has only 11 months of recessionlevel 
benefits in reserve compared with a 22month reserve two decades 
ago the auditors said 
congress decision in 1982 to make states pay interest on money 
they borrowed to maintain benefits has made the system more 
solvent the gao said but at a cost of higher unemployement 
insurance taxes and reduced eligibility 
but ohio employment services administrator ellen obrien told 
the hearing that instead of increasing taxes the government should 
redivide the tax pie so states get a bigger share 
employers who finance this system through the federal 
unemployment tax act are investing enough money to provide adequate 
service she said no new taxes are necessary to return the 
program to its proper funding level 
as the program now works most covered employers pay into the 
system a minimum gross tax of 62 percent on the first 7000 in 
annual wages to a worker on their payroll 
that tax rate would fall to 6 percent at the end of this year 
of the 436 now collected each year per worker 56 goes to the 
federal government and the other 380 goes to the states which 
adjust the actual tax rates on each employer according to the 
firms unemployment experience 
thirtysix states have adopted floors above the mandated 7000 
level ranging from 7100 in connecticut up to 20900 in alaska 
