<TEXT>
the spread of ballistic missiles and other 
modern weaponry in the third world poses a growing threat to us 
security the navys top officer told congress thursday 
adm carlisle ah trost chief of naval operations said that 
while a lowering of superpower tensions made global warfare less 
likely in the 1990s us armed forces will be challenged to 
protect american security in an era of violent peace 
there was a time when conflict in developing countries 
conjured a vision of simple lowtech warfare that would not 
require sophisticated weapons that time has passed trost told 
the house appropriations subcommittee on defense 
today around the globe developing countries are armed with 
first world weapons he said and as a result virtually any 
nation or group of terrorists can bring capable and deadly weapons 
to bear 
thus the united states should remain able to project its naval 
power worldwide he said 
in pleading with congress to avoid big cuts in navy manpower and 
weapons programs trost sounded a theme that lawmakers have heard 
from all service branches in recent weeks the bush administration 
has proposed trimming the defense budget next year by about 2 
percent after inflation but momentum is building in congress to 
cut much more deeply in response to the waning of the cold war 
trost acknowledged that perhaps we are at the end of the cold 
war but he stressed that a wellequipped military still was 
needed to handle hostilities in the third world 
trost said 102 countries in addition to the united states and 
the soviet union now have cruise missiles by the year 2000 at 
least 15 countries will be producing their own ballistic missiles 
he said 
trost also said 14 countries besides the two superpowers have 
chemical weapons and 11 are suspected of developing them he said 
three countries besides the superpowers have bacteriological 
weapons and 15 may be developing them 
