<TEXT>
president bushs proposal to slow the growth 
of medicare by 55 billion next year would hit hospitals too hard 
and should be rejected according to letters released thursday 
signed by a majority of the house and senate 
the overwhelming opposition means that the single biggest piece 
of deficit reduction in the presidents fiscal 1991 budget is in 
serious jeopardy 
the protest letters were not much of a surprise congress has 
been reluctant in recent years to make deep cuts in medicare which 
helps 33 million elderly and disabled people pay hospital and 
doctors bills 
signed by members of both parties and sent to the house and 
senate budget committees the two letters complained that hospitals 
are already under financial pressures 
cuts in the medicare program of the magnitude that the 
president is proposing can only make the situation worse and will 
pose a real threat to health care for the elderly and disabled 
said a letter to senate budget committee chairman james sasser 
dtenn signed by 51 senators 
a similar letter from 227 of the 435 house members to house 
budget committee chairman leon panetta dcalif said bushs plan 
threatens to diminish both access to and quality of care 
medicare is one of the fastestgrowing federal programs it is 
expected to cost 104 billion this year about onetwelfth of the 
entire federal budget and grow to 183 billion by 1995 
in recent years lawmakers searching for ways to reduce the 
budget deficit have responded to pressures from hospitals doctors 
and elderly constituents and been reluctant to make deep medicare 
cuts 
last year bush proposed restraining medicare spending by 5 
billion congress eventually approved 28 billion in savings 
of the 37 billion in deficit cuts the president proposed in the 
1991 budget he released last month the largest piece was the 55 
billion in reduced medicare spending 
