<TEXT>
a foundation honoring black history month won 
initial approval thursday for the design of a memorial to black 
americans who participated in the american revolution 
the memorial which would be the first on the washington mall 
dedicated to blacks honors some 5000 soldiers and freedomseekers 
who have received relatively little recognition from historians 
it was the beginning of the struggle for freedom in america 
said maurice barboza a plainville conn native and president of 
the patriots foundation the group promoting the memorial proposal 
the declaration of independence galvanized the struggle for 
freedom in america 
the national capital memorial commission on thursday unanimously 
approved the design for the memorial which is to be located on the 
mall near the reflecting pool midway between the lincoln memorial 
and the washington monument and not far from the vietnam war 
memorial 
although the memorial will refer only to the revolutionary war 
it will serve as a reminder barboza said of the contribution 
blacks made in the civil war and the vietnam war 
unveiled for the first time in model form thursday the memorial 
consists of 13 figures one for each of the original colonies in 
various roles black americans played during the revolution the 
figures would be made of bronze and placed on grnite pedestals 
the figures would include soldiers and civilians men women and 
children 
