<DOCNO> AP900222-0175 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
business executives and a bush administration 
official said thursday that a national product liability law is 
essential to us competitiveness in the world market 
if we are serious about addressing our nations 
competitiveness we must address the excessive burdens placed on 
american business by our current liability system said wendell 
wilkie ii general counsel for the commerce department 
a federal product liability law would make the rules for doing 
business clear consistent uniform and predictable wilkie 
said in testimony before the senate commerce consumer subcommittee 
state laws are more burdensome and unpredictable than those in 
any of our other trading partners he added 
senator robert kasten rwis author of a bill to establish a 
national law said member nations of the european economic 
community already had adopted uniform product liability guidelines 
which would increase their advantage in global markets 
were going to be in a position very quickly in which germany 
france and england are going to have uniform laws while wisconsin 
minnesota and illinois are going to be further apart kasten said 
kastens bill would create a uniform standard for imposing 
punitive damages in product liability lawsuits and estblish a 
twoyear statute of limitations for most product liability claims 
claims by workers injured by durable goods such as factory 
machinery would have a 25year statute of limitations 
the measure would allow separate trials or settlements of 
punitive damages and compensatory damages and allow companies to 
pay damages in proportion to their responsibility for harm 
businessmen howard fark and robert c holland said change was 
needed in the current system to stop the rapid rise in business 
insurance costs 
wilkie said a uniform law also would reduce transaction 
costs attorneys fees damage awards and other court costs 
associated with lawsuits involving potentially dangerous products 
but commerce committee chairman ernest hollings dsc blamed 
businesses for the rise in insurance and legal costs and challenged 
the need for federal intervention in product liability 
others including vincent l mckusick chief judge of the maine 
supreme court and michael box an alabama state representative 
argued that the federal government should aid state enforcement 
instead of tinkering unnecessarily with state law 
hollings cited a 1989 congressional study that showed about 
half the plaintiffs attorneys received no fee 
the study by the general accounting office also found that most 
punitive damages are overturned on appeal said hollings adding 
this goes to the heart of transaction costs 
the gao reviewed court records of 305 product liability cases 
resolved in trials from 198385 in arizona massachusetts 
missouri north dakota and south carolina 
proponents acknowledge the kasten bill might not directly reduce 
transaction costs but said the bill would encourage faster 
resolution of disputes because it requires that lawyers who refuse 
reasonable outof court settlements must pay all attorneys fees 
congress has attempted to develop a federal product liability 
law since the 1970s and president bush made it an administration 
legislative priority in his state of the union address last month 
</TEXT>
