<DOCNO> AP900222-0194 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
union oil agreed thursday to a 555 
million court settlement stemming from the pollution of san pablo 
bay in what lawyers called the largest civil penalty in the 
history of the federal clean water act 
the settlement resolves a longstanding dispute over pollution 
that environmentalists contended took place between april 1979 and 
february 1988 in the bay which is located about 15 miles northeast 
of here and is part of san francisco bay 
were elated said attorney stephan volker of the sierra 
club legal defense fund inc volker who filed suit against the 
company in 1984 credited the litigation with exposing and halting 
systematic manipulation of the selfmonitoring program on which 
the clean water act is based 
this should send a strong message to other polluters clean up 
your operations or face the prospect of being hauled into court and 
paying a substantial penalty volker said 
john barg the attorney handling the case for union which has 
been acquired by unocal declined to comment on the settlement 
unocal spokesman jeff callender emphasized that the settlement did 
not constitute an admission of fault 
the company maintains that many of the alleged violations are 
the result of misunderstandings regarding provisions of the clean 
water act he said 
we remained confident of our position but the case has dragged 
on for six years and we felt it was time to put it behind us 
callender said 
union oil employees testified during the dispute that the 
company repeatedly and deliberately violated the terms of its waste 
water discharge permit and failed to report the violations volker 
said 
the settlement followed years of legal battles although the 
courts initially found in favor of unions position subsequent 
rulings went against the company 
in december 1988 us district court judge samuel conti ruled 
that union oil had violated its federal waste discharge permit 200 
times including nine bypasses of its treatment plant in the town 
of rodeo a trial had been scheduled for this month 
the wastes that flowed into the bay included phenols and other 
potentially cancercausing substances such as benzene toluene 
acetone and trichloroethylene conti said the company had saved 
from 20 million to 60 million by failing to install adequate 
treatment equipment 
the penalty was described by the sierra club legal defense fund 
as the highest ever paid as the result of a civil lawsuit under the 
federal clean water act the previous high was 32 million awarded 
in a new jersey case last year 
the settlement includes 272 million that unocal will give the 
trust for public land for acquisition and restoration of wetlands 
around san francisco bay 1 million to the environmental 
protection agency to study the removal of dredge spoils from the 
san francisco bay 500000 to the state of california water 
pollution cleanup and abatement fund for emergency pollution 
cleanup and 133 million in scldf court costs 
state attorney general john van de kamp whose office 
participated in the litigation hailed the settlement 
californias strict water quality law was enacted precisely to 
prevent this type of environmental abuse he said our evidence 
showed that unocal repeatedly disregarded this law both by numerous 
waste discharge violations and by failing to report them as 
required 
the company spent 64 million last year to upgrade its 
wastewater treatment facilities in the contra costa county town of 
rodeo callender said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

