<TEXT>
with the argentine austral losing 
value by as much as 25 percent a day the us dollar has become 
the preferred currency in many buenos aires shops stores and 
showrooms 
some businesses refuse to accept the austral altogether many 
others price their goods only in dollars but allow customers to pay 
in australs at their current value against the dollar 
the price list arrives in dollars and we charge customers in 
dollars because the factory insists it be paid in dollars said 
roberto molinelli 48 a ford salesman 
when the distributor delivers a case of champagne i pay in 
cash said ernesto merin 24 owner of an upscale boutique if 
not i have a week or two weeks to pay never 30 days anymore 
but when i pay its in dollars or the dollar amount in australs 
argentines have been stashing dollars away as a hedge against a 
soaring inflation an estimated 5 billion is tucked away in 
strongboxes or under mattresses and 50 billion more is in overseas 
banks 
during the past year the austral has lost 99 percent of its 
value against the dollar 
in february 1989 it took just 17 australs to buy one dollar 
at one point this february it took 4100 meaning the dollar 
increased more than 24000 percent in value 
argentines salaries generally are increased monthly in line 
with inflation which rose by 4924 percent in 1989 and 8124 
percent the past 12month period 
for some time automobiles apartments jewelry furs airline 
tickets and other expensive items have been priced in dollars by 
retailers wary of inflation 
but as the costofliving this year approached 80 percent a 
month stores that sell records leather handbags eyeglasses 
gifts dinnerware and a host of similar items many made in 
argentina now charge in dollars or the equivalent in australs 
we use dollars as a base said optician jorge romero 26 
whose shop is on fashionable florida st in downtown buenos aires 
its so much easier otherwise wed be changing prices several 
times a day 
dentists doctors lawyers economic consultants car mechanics 
carpenters and tv repairmen even housemaids charge in dollars or 
the equivalent in australs 
unions representing schoolteachers have requested that they be 
paid the equivalent of 100 a month the government has ignored 
such requests because it lacks the dollars to comply 
perhaps the biggest problem for business has been what price to 
charge 
i called the factory last month to find out how much it would 
cost to replace some games they sold me said merin the boutique 
owner they quoted me a price in dollars when i checked the 
price i was selling them for in australs i found i was selling at 
cost now i price everything in dollars 
when inflation roared to a monthly record of 197 percent in 
july pharmacies hardware and other stores shut down rather than 
sell too low 
that along with the withholding of deliveries by distributors 
and hoarding by customers has disrupted the commercial supply 
chain across this nation of 31 million people as has the refusal 
of most stores now to accept credit cards 
the apparent solution was to price goods directly in dollars 
but that has put the vast majority of argentines who earn 
salaries in australs at a severe disadvantage 
after i got paid for january i paid my rent and utility 
bills then divided the rest by the number of days in the month 
said a newspaper reporter now what i have left is hardly enough 
to eat on 
typical salaries in january ranged from 200000 australs for 
teachers and other public servants to 1 million australs for lower 
level managers and shopowners the dollar value of those salaries 
eroded from 100500 on feb 1 to 50250 three weeks later 
this will be the worst year for me said juan dainese 43 
manager of one of buenos aires oldest bookstores people dont 
have any money its as simple as that 
