<TEXT>
trucks rumble down dirt trails to service 
the wells that have sprouted in this dusty cactusfilled backwood 
dealmakers cram the local hotels and one eatery has installed 
tabletop telephones for them 
oil the onetime backbone of the texas economy that fractured 
in the late 1980s because of a world supply glut has mended 
spurred by new technology and higher prices this part of oil 
country is growing at a pace unseen in years 
some have dubbed it the new spindletop recalling the first 
texas gusher because record flows have come from wells tapped late 
last year using horizontal drilling techniques that maximize 
chances of a find 
but more cautious folks humbled by shortlived booms in the 
past arent so effusive 
you dont see all the new pickups running up and down the road 
that you did during past upswings said inez asher a former 
mayor of dilley the town of 2500 people is at the center of the 
pearsall field activity about 80 miles southwest of san antonio 
ms asher herself was about to leave dilley until she returned 
from a vacation last august to find a resurgence 
land lease prices rose from 50 an acre last year to as much as 
450 the county courthouse in pearsall stays open late at night to 
accommodate landmen searching records 
at the porterhouse inn in pearsall one of the few hotels in the 
area rooms are at a premium one resembled a miniature office 
with a map of the area taped to the wall and a typewriter nearby 
we could rent 60 more rooms if we had em said a desk clerk 
rental housing has been swallowed up by workers coming to join 
the boom 
oil has brought an opportunity to get a quality job said 
pearsall city manager andres garza jr oil rig workers earn about 
9 an hour nearly triple what local farmhands make 
at pappas a truckstop and bus station along interstate 35 
phones were installed at the tables for the land dealers who gather 
there 
sales tax collections have doubled bank deposits are up 20 
percent 
so is traffic were really beginning to need a red light 
ms asher said 
business has tripled and its all oil said innkeeper 
shirley young she and her husband run the dilley hotel and 
restaurant a bedandbreakfast inn now base camp for many oilmen 
once we just figured we were going to dry up and blow away 
she said now its hard to keep an ample food supply 
booms have been seen before in the austin chalk the geological 
formation that includes the pearsall field but the area earned the 
nickname heartbreak field because one well would produce and 
another nearby would come up dry 
the oil there is found in vertical fractures that left little 
room for mistake 
horizontal wells which make a 90degree turn more than a mile 
underground can link several vertical formations increasing 
chances for success the main question is how long the increased 
production rates will be maintained some experts expect the wells 
may expire faster than vertical wells 
while horizontal wells are credited for the austin chalk 
recovery the rebound elsewhere in texas is linked to oil prices 
that have remained relatively steady at more than 20 a barrel for 
months which is considered a sign of strength in the energy market 
the oil industry has been hoping for a return to this stability 
since prices collapsed to about 10 a barrel in 1986 weakened by 
the increased production of the organization of petroleum exporting 
countries 
that drop traumatized oil drillers and especially hurt texas 
which had been thriving based on projections of oil fetching 30 
and 40 a barrel or more 
many drillers simply cut their losses by capping wells some 
sought bankruptcy and others liquidated unemployment soared land 
values tumbled banks faltered and the state became a nationwide 
symbol of hard times 
the oil rebound conversely has encouraged many companies to 
increase spending for exploration the resurgence even has drillers 
and service companies worried about finding qualified people to 
work the rigs also in somewhat short supply 
for the first time in four or five years the industry last 
december ran short of rigs used to improve existing wells said 
harry spannous director of the permian basin petroleum 
association the association is based in midland headquarters of 
the west texas oilfield containing about a quarter of the oil and 
gas reserves in the lower 48 states 
bakerhughes incs rig count an index of exploratory 
operations reflects the new activity as of feb 2 83 rigs were 
working in the texas section of the permian basin vs 57 a year 
ago in east texas 57 were looking for oil and gas compared with 
39 last year 
those increases are slight compared with the growth in the 
pearsall field one rig last year 38 now production has more than 
doubled and new discoveries are announced weekly 
oryx energy co of dallas pioneered the process in the region 
persuading the industryregulating texas railroad commission to 
increase allowables the amount of oil that can be pumped from the 
ground and the space required between wells 
since oryx went before the commission in august revealing its 
success with horizontal drilling companies have flocked to the 
field even though oryx had acquired leases on much of the prime 
drilling area before showing its hand said jim roberts the 
companys vice president of production 
although rivals are drilling scores of wells nobody has matched 
oryxs perfect record at finding oil with horizontal wells 
still there have been some spectacular results topped by 
charlie winn 
the oldstyle wildcatter has tapped two major wells on an 
8900acre lease and has three more under way the first well is 
producing 5472 barrels of oil a day a state record and the 
second is producing better than 3600 barrels 
the oil business is fun again winn said 
</TEXT>
