<TEXT>
brazil is second only to the 
united states in the number of reported aids cases but the deadly 
disease may spread more rapidly here 
i wouldnt want to be brazils health minister said 
mathilde krim of the american foundation for aids research 
theres a probability the aids problem here will rapidly worsen 
and there are few resources to help 
this south american country of 150 million people is in 
transition between thirdworld and developedworld aids 
patterns said peter fischinger vice president for research at the 
medical university of south carolina 
brazil is closer to the developedworld model but the 
possibility of brazilian heterosexuals becoming infected by 
establishedrisk groups is very great fischinger said krim 
agreed there is a lot of multipartner sex activity and also a 
large number of bisexuals 
the first victims in the developed world according to 
fischinger were gay men who still account for 45 percent of 
cases before the disease spread to intravenous drug users and 
heterosexuals in africa and the caribbean a large majority of 
victims were and are heterosexuals 
brazil with 9555 reported aids cases through december 1989 is 
the worlds no 2 aids country after the united states which had 
113211 reported cases according to the world health organization 
france is no 3 with 8025 reported cases followed by uganda with 
7375 
at a gathering last month of more than 50 specialists sponsored 
by french brazilian and us health organizations lair guerra de 
macedo rodrigues head of the health ministrys national division 
for sexually transmitted diseases and aids said brazil has made 
important progress in battling the disease 
sixty percent of brazils 6 million transfusions in 1988 were 
with blood untested for the aids virus she said nine percent of 
the aids cases in brazil were caused by transfusions vs about 1 
percent in developed countries 
the situation is still not ideal but weve tested 70 percent 
of samples in blood banks and the risk has been greatly reduced 
she said adding that the risk of infection via transfusions still 
is 1 in 40000 compared with 1 in 250000 in the united states 
brazils economic crisis with inflation running almost 2000 
percent will mean a 60 percent cut this year in the divisions 
1989 budget of 104 million ms rodrigues said were doing the 
best we can with limited resources 
brazil was slower in acting to combat the disease than other 
countries said michel kazatchkine a french researcher the first 
cases were reported in brazil in 1983 but the government did not 
place a priority on combating the virus until 1987 
in france and the united states homosexuals are well organized 
while brazilian machismo keeps gay groups far more discreet 
she said in france there are a large number of support groups 
with hot lines shelters meetings and other assistance in 1985 
65 precent of reported aids victims were gay men the percentage of 
gay men who account for newly diagnosed cases is less than 45 
percent today 
figures in brazil also show a lower percentage of gays in new 
cases but that may merely mean more rapid growth among others 
in 1986 in brazil krim said there were 117 men carrying the 
aids virus for every woman carrying it that ratio has dropped to 7 
to 1 
ten percent of brazilian aids victims are heterosexuals 
compared with an estimated 5 percent in the united states 
three other factors threaten brazils heterosexual community 
kazatchkine said young brazilians tend to be more promiscuous and 
have less access to aids education and preventive measures than 
their counterparts in developed nations millions of street 
kids work as prostitutes and also have sex with their comrades 
and in part because of the economic crisis more women work at 
least parttime as prostitutes 
a final problem is an increase in the number of brazilians who 
contract aids via intravenous drug use now 128 percent of the 
total krim said 
