<TEXT>
a planned price hike by one of the worlds largest newsprint 
producers is unlikely to take effect because supply is plentiful 
and growing at a brisk rate analysts and newspaper officials say 
abitibiprice inc notified customers this week it plans to 
raise the list price of newsprint by 35 a metric ton or 54 
percent to 685 a metric ton 
any broad increase would be the first since an industrywide 66 
percent price hike on jan 1 1988 while the list price has 
remained steady actual selling prices and newsprint makers 
profits have declined 
edward ahern a marketing director for abitibis sales unit 
said the increase is effective june 1 
the torontobased company the worlds second largest newsprint 
maker behind fletcher challenge of new zealand told customers the 
increase is necessary because it is losing money on current 
newsprint sales ahern said 
i sent all our suppliers a letter saying i think its 
ridiculous said homer taylor vice president of supply for 
knightridder inc one of the nations largest newspaper groups 
with consumption and operating rates dropping and supply 
increasing and discounts increasing it just doesnt make any 
sense 
we dont think its the right time said bill hee 
purchasing manager for gannett supply corp owned by the largest 
us newspaper chain its not based on supply and demand there 
is plenty of paper around 
taylor said the price announcement was a repeat of last years 
failed attempt to increase prices and conditions in the industry 
have deteriorated since then advertising linage is down 
substantially and consumption at most of knightridders more than 
30 newspapers is flat to lower he said 
the american newspaper publishers association said daily 
consumption declined 03 percent industrywide last year 
consumption fell 51 percent in the northeast where newspaper 
retail advertising dropped substantially due to financial troubles 
at store chain owner campeau corp it rose 51 percent in the west 
however 
demand for newsprint has held up mainly because knightridder 
and other newspaper companies are stockpiling supplies in 
anticipation of possible labor problems in canada taylor said 
mill workers in canada have asked for a hefty wage increase and 
have threatened to strike if demands are not met when their 
contracts expire on april 30 
conditions are worse this year in terms of making a price 
increase stick taylor said they see all this purchasing and 
are reading it as consumption 
knightridder has increased its inventories to about 50 days 
from 36 days taylor said gannett recently raised its inventories 
about three days to 45 days hee said 
industry analysts also are skeptical that the increase will take 
effect 
wishful thinking said george b adler analyst for smith 
barney harris upham amp co in new york theres too much 
newsprint capacity excessive 
adler said north american capacity is continuing to increase in 
1990 and is not expected to slow until next year 
meanwhile many canadian newsprint makers are experiencing 
problems because of widespread discounting a common industry 
practice 
while the current list price is 650 a metric ton the actual 
selling price to customers is about 530 a ton adler said 
abitibi on monday reported a fourthquarter loss and lower 1989 
profits and blamed it on lower newsprint prices the results follow 
abitibis warning to employees last month of possible mill 
shutdowns and job cuts this year 
nonetheless part of the price increase could take effect 
particularly if canadian employees decide to strike said robert 
duncan analyst with wood gundy inc in toronto eastern canada is 
the worlds largest single source of newsprint 
 
