resorts international inc says the 
twoyear casino license renewal it received from state regulators 
will help it shake free of bankruptcy and recover from the decline 
that has hit the boardwalks first gambling hall 
the casino control commission said wednesday in its unanimous 
decision to renew the license that the gaming company must report 
monthly on its troubled finances 
company president david c hanlon said resorts the parent 
company to merv griffins resorts casino hotel in atlantic city 
can live with those restrictions 
the conditions are essentially financial reporting 
conditions he said hopefully two years from now well be a 
strong company 
as for now the company is trying to restructure its 
debtriddled finances in bankruptcy court which the commission 
said it considered in its decision 
the mere filing of a chapter 11 action does not in and of 
itself warrant a conclusion that a company lacks financial 
stability said acting commission chairwoman valerie armstrong 
the bankruptcy action is but one albeit significant factor 
she said resorts had shown during commission hearings last week 
that it could become financially stable within the twoyear license 
period under a flat growth scenario 
last month resorts won 143 million from gamblers an 11 
percent drop from the 161 million registered in january 1989 
according to commission figures the casinos win for all of 
1989 dropped 64 percent to 2274 million compared to the year 
before win is the amount of money gamblers lose and does not take 
into account expenses it is not profit 
under the flat growth forecast resorts will post a 500000 
cash deficit at the end of the year because of an extensive 
refurbishing program the commission said in its ruling 
the commission imposed conditions recommended by the division of 
gaming enforcement that resorts file monthly balance sheets income 
statements and statements of cash flow and working capital resorts 
officials also must advise regulators on a monthly basis of 
significant deviations from financial projections and from prior 
financial performance 
the commission stopped short however of requiring the casino 
to report daily or weekly or to set a specific cash balance that 
would trigger the imposition of restricted accounts to ensure that 
wages taxes and progressive jackpots are paid 
hanlon said he was pleased with the decision and confident the 
opening april 2 of the neighboring taj mahal casino would reverse 
the decline of the first gaming hall to open on the boardwalk in 
1978 
ironically the taj mahal a property originally owned by 
resorts led to some of its financial problems as construction 
costs since 1983 until its sale to donald trump in 1988 diverted 
money from resorts and its capital expenditures 
hanlon emphasized the importance of resorts plans to win 
approval of its restucturing plan from bondholders and a bankruptcy 
judge the plan seeks to shed about 400 million of the 927 
million that griffin assumed to finance his november 1988 purchase 
of the property from trump griffin sold trump the taj mahal in 
return 
our first priority is restructuring hanlon said after the 
hearing were going full speed ahead with it 
anthony j parrillo the director of the division of gaming 
enforcement said the division was satisfied with the ruling but 
took issue with the commissions refusal to set a 75 million cash 
balance trigger or to consider a worstcase scenario of less than 
flat growth 
ms armstrong said the commission could reopen the license 
process any time during the next two years however she also said 
resorts had not hit the depth of the nowdefunct elsinores 
atlantis casino hotel which in may became the first casino to 
close its doors after the commission found the gaming hall was 
insolvent 
