<TEXT>
in yet another step to cope with sagging 
profits and a sluggish market for personal computers apple 
computer will lay off 3 percent of its work force as part of a 
major costcutting campaign 
although the transition we are experiencing is by no means an 
easy one it is necessary to build an even stronger business 
foundation for the future john sculley apples chairman and 
chief executive officer said in a statement wednesday 
since december apple has been embroiled in a tumultuous 
restructuring that has included the resignation of the head of the 
companys domestic division also the companys new products 
developer jeanlouis gassee reportedly is preparing to depart 
the company also has implemented pay freezes cuts in 
profitsharing and even dropped company parties 
analysts say apple must deal with rising customer 
dissatisfaction sagging profits management turmoil and worsening 
employee morale 
this is an extremely important year for apple particularly in 
terms of product development and stability in the executive 
suite said benny lorenzo an analyst at volpe covington amp welty 
in san francisco 
the most significant problem for apple is its eroding position 
as the biggest supplier of easytouse computers a position that 
has allowed it to charge substantially higher prices than 
competitors like ibm and compaq computers 
microsoft has released its windows programs a graphical 
interface that attempts to offer a userfriendly alternative to the 
macintosh interface 
hewlettpackard co also has unveiled a similar system called 
new wave 
analysts say apples products are still easier to use but not 
as much as they once were 
separately on thursday apple announced immediate cuts of 10 to 
17 percent off the suggested retail prices on all models of its 
macintosh se and se30 personal computers and laserwriter iint and 
iintx printers sold domestically 
david hancock senior vice president of marketing said the cuts 
would allow apple bring the macintosh personal computing 
experience to more people 
apple is now paying the price for decisions they made several 
years ago when it elected to go for shortterm profit gain rather 
than taking advantage of its leading position to go for greater 
market share said jonathan seybold publisher of los 
angelesbased seybold report on desktop publishing 
sculley blamed the 400 layoffs on a slowdown in the us 
personal computer industry which after three years of doubledigit 
growth is expected to grow no more than 9 percent in 1990 
but analysts have faulted the worlds secondlargest personal 
computer maker for neglecting and even alienating its traditional 
customers 
apple failed to meet a critical customer need by not introducing 
an inexpensive updated version of its original macintosh which has 
loyal users worldwide 
instead apple introduced expensive macintosh models for 
corporate use where profits are greater 
after numerous delays apple also released a portable computer 
considered by many as costly bulky and difficult to read 
apples stock rose 50 cents to 34 a share in national 
overthecounter trading wednesday 
most of the cuts in apples 13500member work force which 
become effective in two months will be made in domestic marketing 
and distribution and in personnel finance community and 
government affairs and customer service 
the company will continue hiring workers for research and 
development and for its domestic sales force hirings also will 
continue in apples european and pacific divisions 
most everybody left at the company is making a big sigh of 
relief but apple will still have the problem of low morale in its 
product development division that remains to be corrected said 
abigail christopher of international data co a market researcher 
in framingham mass 
apple had sales of 53 billion last year up about 25 percent 
from 1988 
in the final three months of last year however sales rose only 
6 percent and profits fell 11 percent that was the third 
consecutive quarter of lower profits and came during the 
traditionally strong christmas season 
dealers reportedly were angered that apple did comparatively 
little holiday marketing for its 13yearold apple ii line and 
support products prompting customer fears that the company would 
abandon the machine that catapulted it to prominence 
lack of effective marketing also apparently crimped sales of the 
macintosh plus and macintosh se the least expensive products in 
the macintosh line 
many apple employees increasingly have been complaining about 
the companys turmoil especially the numerous restructurings since 
cofounder steven p jobs was ousted in a 1985 power struggle with 
sculley 
these latest moves are basically the undoing of the last 
reorganization and thats been the pattern said seybold 
