<TEXT>
us officials today accused japan of not doing 
enough to reform deeprooted business traditions and economic 
behavior that contribute to japans 49 billion trade surplus with 
the united states 
after the first of two days of trade talks members of the us 
delegation complained that japanese plans to help ease the trade 
imbalance hadnt gone as far as we hoped 
it is very important to note that some progress has been made 
but frankly much more needs to be done said a member of the 
us delegation who briefed reporters on condition he not be 
identified 
us trade negotiators had said going into todays session that 
they expected quick results in addressing the underlying causes of 
the persistent usjapan trade imbalance 
us trade negotiators are under heavy pressure from congress to 
demonstrate progress in the 9monthold talks which are aimed at 
changing deeprooted factors in both economies that contribute to 
the us trade deficit with japan 
us trade representative carla hills has said she expects a 
plan of action and a realistic down payment that shows resolve on 
both sides by this summer 
the 49 billion us trade deficit with japan accounted for 45 
percent of 1989s 10858 billion us deficit 
in two earlier rounds of talks us officials said japans high 
savings and investment rates its land policies exclusionary 
business practices and corporate alliances inefficient retail 
distribution networks and pricing mechanisms all act as trade 
barriers 
japan in turn said inadequate savings and investment in the 
united states shortterm corporate strategies by us firms 
ineffective labor training and education and insufficient export 
promotion were structural factors underlying the trade imbalance 
after talks in september and november us officials complained 
that the japanese side had shown little evidence of flexibility or 
willingness to act quickly while japanese officials said such 
farreaching changes could not be expected overnight 
japanese officials today explained a recently announced program 
involving tax tariff and import promotion policies nhk reported 
the measures include tax incentives for importers and elimination 
of tariffs on 1004 items 
the immediate us reaction to the japanese presentation was 
severe nhk said 
an official of the ministry of international trade and industry 
speaking on condition of anonymity concluded after the days talks 
that it would take more time for the two sides to iron out their 
differences 
us officials had earlier reacted with caution to the measures 
expressing skepticism over whether the importboosting policies 
would really increase purchases of foreignmade goods 
another key area of contention is japans large retail store 
law which requires firms wanting to open department stores or 
supermarkets to obtain consent from existing smaller stores that 
are generally reluctant to face competition from larger more 
efficient retail outlets 
the lengthy complicated process of opening a large store takes 
about 10 years 
in addition to protecting less efficient retailers and thereby 
driving up prices the us side says the law tends to restrict 
imports by limiting the number of foreignowned stores and by 
restricting openings of large stores that tend to sell more 
imported products than traditional small stores 
williams said the us side would call for abolition or revision 
of the law 
washington is also likely to urge an easing of laws restricting 
use of bank credit cards while department stores and finance 
companies allow incremental payments on credit purchases made with 
bank credit cards must be paid off entirely within one month a 
regulation that us officials say tends to restrict overall 
consumer spending and therefore spending on imports 
on friday us officials are expected to explain washingtons 
plans to increase low savings and investment rates and to bolster 
the competitiveness of us firms 
</TEXT>
