and office workers did not immediately return telephone calls 
seeking comment 
gravley said the company received a letter today saying the 
strike would take place the rankandfile earlier had authorized a 
strike 
gravley said the company which has been advertising for 
permanent replacement drivers in anticipation of a strike would 
continue to operate 
we have 600 people in school and are still taking 
applications he said 
the two sides had been negotiating since friday in phoenix 
where the union is based but remained far apart on wage issues 
joint meetings friday and monday plus separate sessions with a 
federal mediator on tuesday failed to result in an agreement 
gravley said 
the company taken private three years ago in two deals totaling 
about 470 million had offered a threeyear contract worth about 
63 million gravely said the union initially had sought a pact 
valued at 561 million but reduced that to 475 million 
the union wanted wage increases of 66 percent over the life of 
the contract including a 50 percent raise in the first year 
greyhound offered a firstyear increase of 7 percent currently 
the average bus driver makes 24743 a year according to the 
company 
