<DOCNO> AP900222-0243 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
while some grand old american retailers have 
stumbled into bankruptcy court and others simply have vanished one 
major department store is thriving with its founders 
greatgrandchildren in charge 
of the three major us department store chains controlled by 
descendents 122yearold strawbridge amp clothier is the oldest and 
the only one to last through four generations of potential sibling 
spats and inheritance squabbles 
strawbridges has grown steadily through the takeover obsession 
of the 1980s in which many rivals became sodden with the debt 
obligations of new owners some of whom didnt know much about the 
business 
perhaps the most notorious example is the campeau corp of 
canada which bought bloomingdales jordan marsh and several other 
famous chains in the late 1980s for billions of dollars in borrowed 
money then sought bankruptcy protection for them last month 
because it couldnt repay debts 
strawbridges by contrast has expanded with its own money over 
the past decade it has added four department stores and 10 
discount stores in the philadelphia area considered one of the 
birthplaces of modernday retailing the company has 13 department 
stores and 23 discount stores in pennsylvania new jersey and 
delaware 
its presence is a beacon for philadelphia shoppers who have 
witnessed lit brothers and gimbels go broke and wanamakers the 
countrys first retail department store sold twice strawbridges 
has been as steady as the modest quaker family that runs it 
eighteen of its 20 top executives have been with the company at 
least 25 years and more than half its 110 midlevel managers have 
worked for the store 15 years or more strawbridges claims one of 
the lowest turnover rates on the sales floor 
it has surpassed traditional big brother wanamakers as the king 
of the citys department stores wanamakers coincidentally once 
again is for sale 
for its 1989 fiscal year ended in july strawbridges earned 
279 million on sales of 9211 million the companys sales are 
expected to exceed 1 billion in fiscal 1990 
while many competitors profits are drained by creditors or 
retained for a parent company strawbridges has reinvested 
earnings in expansion and upkeep 
the independence of the company is the major contributing 
factor to what we think of and call the uniquely personalized 
character of strawbridge amp clothier francis r strawbridge iii 
chairman once said in response to a lawsuit filed by an outside 
investor who wanted to buy the company in 1986 
his uncle and family patriarch g stockton strawbridge 
described the effort to remain family controlled as an ever 
present objective comparable to inhaling and exhaling 
in an effort to avoid attracting the attention of wouldbe 
raiders the camerashy strawbridge family resists press interviews 
about the business 
one executive who spoke on condition of anonymity attributed 
the familys unity to good fortune as well as g stockton 
strawbridges efforts at maintaining a tightknit relationship 
strawbridge amp clothier is now run nearly entirely by the 
strawbridge family 
the clothier family whose wealth was devastated by the great 
depression sold most voting shares in the 1930s a clothier sits 
on the board of directors but is the only descendent of the 
founder involved with the stores 
for family businesses surviving beyond three generations can be 
difficult because interest in running the business often wanes from 
one generation to the next said ronald h drucker a family 
business consultant with philadelphiabased accountants laventhol amp 
horwath 
the problems pop up more in the third generation than the 
second said dean schuckman a partner and management consultant 
with the accounting firm price waterhouse if the family is more 
sharing of the founders vision youre going to find less conflict 
among the siblings 
for strawbridge amp clothier fertility has helped the 
strawbridges have been able to pick those interested and talented 
from a large pool of offspring 
strawbridge children arent encouraged to enter the business 
but if they want to pursue a career in retailing they have to work 
at least a year at another major department store before entering 
strawbridges training program 
four members of the fourth generation work at the company one 
fifth generation member daughter of company president peter s 
strawbridge joined the advertising department in january after 
three years at filenes in boston 
francis r strawbridge iii his brother david w strawbridge 
personnel vice president cousin peter strawbridge and his brother 
steven l strawbridge treasurer and secretary have 12 children 
among them and there are scores of other fifth generation children 
two other major department store chains still are family 
operated dillards based in little rock ark started in 1938 
and is still run by 75yearold founder william dillard nordstrom 
inc based in seattle is operated by the grandsons of the 
founder who started the firm in 1901 
strawbridges first opened in 1868 on the site of thomas 
jeffersons old us secretary of state office in downtown 
philadelphia 
justus c strawbridge then 30 took his landlords soninlaw 
isaac h clothier also 30 on as a partner in his fledgling dry 
goods store 
the threestory house at the corner of eighth and market streets 
has grown to take up most of the block and anchor a downtown 
shopping mall 
since then the company has had many offers but faced its most 
serious challenge in 1984 when a new york investor named ronald 
baron was amassing shares in the company for a takeover attempt 
two years later the strawbridges defeated baron by purchasing a 
crucial bloc of stock from dissident family member robert e 
strawbridge iii who appeared ready to sell the cost of retaining 
family control was 40 million 
as an additional defense the company has established a 
preferred class of stock that has 10 votes per share common stock 
has one vote per share the board decides who can buy preferred 
stock 
an executive who spoke on condition of anonymity said the 
company has considered two or three times a debtfinanced 
restructuring to protect itself from more takeover attempts but 
that alternative has been rejected by the family because it would 
divert too much money into debt payments 
without anxious junkbond holders waiting to be paid or 
shortterm investors looking for quick gains strawbridges has 
been able to spend its profits on store improvements and 
maintenance 
in plowing back those earnings they are able to keep our 
stores up to date fashionable attractive exciting and places 
where people really like to shop the lone clother board member 
isaac h clothier iv once said during the takeover fight with 
baron nothing looks dinty at strawbridge and clothier 
</TEXT>
