<TEXT>
although the british are indisputably the worlds 
biggest tea fans preliminary estimates released thursday show that 
britain for the first time lost its position as the worlds top tea 
importer to the soviet union 
moscows tea imports rose 92000 metric tons last year to a 
record 227000 tons pushing the soviet union into first place 
according to the independent business information concern the 
economist intelligence unit 
in its latest review of key commodity markets the economist 
intelligence unit estimated british imports totaled about 160000 
tons last year 
the romebased food and agriculture organization put british 
imports at 116400 metric tons in the first nine months of 1989 
down from 125100 in the same 1988 period 
the soviet union has increased the amount of tea it imports 
steadily since 1986 when its own tea crop grown in georgia was 
severely damaged by fallout from the chernobyl nuclear disaster 
particularly heavy soviet tea buying toward the end of last 
year which coincided with crop problems in india sri lanka and 
other key tea exporting countries helped push world wholesale 
prices to threeyear highs 
at the peak last october the average price paid at the weekly 
london tea auction hit 2885 per ton the price at this weeks 
sale was at a sixmonth low of 2095 according to the tea 
brokers association 
the price decline is the result of improved supplies following a 
recovery in production in india and sri lanka toward the end of 
last year traders said 
the prospect of a supply shortfall for the second year running 
could lift the average price in 1990 to 2360 a ton from 2103 
last year 
the economist intelligence unit said it expected soviet imports 
to hold steady this year because it would be difficult to cut 
supplies during the present upheavals shortages of food and 
other goods have exasperated soviet citizens and aggravated 
political turmoil at a time of serious unrest in some soviet 
republics 
