<TEXT>
us officials engaged in trade negotiations with 
japan said thursday that country has not done enough to address the 
underlying causes of the persistent usjapan trade imbalance 
at the conclusion of the first of two days of talks us 
delegates complained that japans plans to help ease its 49 
billion trade surplus with the united states hadnt gone as far 
as we hoped 
in particular japan is moving too slowly in changing its high 
savings and investment rates land policies exclusionary business 
practices inefficient retail distribution networks and pricing 
mechanisms us officials said 
it is very important to note that some progress has been made 
but frankly much more needs to be done said a member of the 
us delegation who briefed reporters on condition he not be 
identified by name 
on friday it is the united states turn to explain what it is 
doing to change american practices that contribute to the 
imbalance us officials said they would outline washingtons 
plans to increase the low us savings and investment rates and to 
bolster the competitiveness of american firms 
the talks called the structural impediments initiative were 
launched last may after years of exchange rate adjustments and 
other steps failed to significantly reduce the imbalance 
this round of talks originally set for early january was 
postponed at japans request until after national parliamentary 
elections sunday that kept the liberal democratic party in power 
because of the election we did lose time and we believe 
strongly that we need to get moving quickly and move forward to 
some solutions said deputy us trade representative s linn 
williams 
after the delay us officials said they expected japanese 
leaders to produce plans for both longterm measures and immediate 
actions to tackle structural trade problems 
us trade negotiators are under heavy pressure to demonstrate 
progress in the talks to stave off protectionist trade legislation 
in congress 
the political realities are such that sii is not viewed 
with patience and therefore if that process is going to yield 
results it needs to yield a sort of midterm dividend payment very 
quickly david c mulford us under secretary for international 
affairs told a business audience in new york thursday we would 
all lose if the failure to remove these impediments leads to more 
rather than less protection 
us officials say japans high savings and investment rates 
its land policies exclusionary business practices inefficient 
retail distribution networks and pricing mechanisms all indirectly 
restrain trade 
on thursday japanese officials explained measures in a draft 
budget before parliament to boost staffing of japans fair trade 
commission its antimonopoly enforcement authority to increase 
spending on public infrastructure such as roads and sewers and to 
reform the retail distribution system 
they also explained revisions of japans land use law aimed at 
curbing real estate speculation and increasing the supply of 
available land in urban areas 
the us side contends that excessive land prices in japan drive 
up the cost of doing business making it harder for foreign firms 
to sell their products here 
we carefully explained the steps that were taking and in many 
areas received an assessment from the us side but other areas 
remain where there were still differences its going to take more 
time said an official of the ministry of international trade and 
industry speaking on condition of anonymity 
members of the us delegation said the presentations 
represented new actions and some progress but its clear to us 
they havent gone as far as we hoped with bold new thinking 
too often today instead of new ideas on how to solve the 
problems we heard simply a defense of the status quo one us 
official said 
us officials said they made a number of suggestions on 
possible revisions of japans large retail store law 
the law requires firms wanting to open department stores or 
supermarkets to obtain consent from existing momandpop stores 
generally reluctant to face competition from larger stores 
in addition to protecting less efficient retailers and thereby 
driving up prices the us side says the law tends to restrict 
imports by limiting the number of foreignowned stores and by 
restricting openings of large japanese stores that tend to sell 
more imported products than traditional small stores 
after structural talks in september and november us officials 
complained that the japanese side had shown little evidence of 
flexibility or willingness to act quickly while japanese officials 
said such farreaching changes could not be expected overnight 
williams characterized the latest talks as neither successful 
nor disappointing but he said the talks were on the right 
track in many ways i wish we had gotten on the track earlier 
japan says us problems contributing to the trade imbalance 
include inadequate savings and investment the shortterm nature of 
us corporate strategies ineffective labor training and education 
and insufficient export promotion 
both delegations said they expected to produce an interim report 
on progress in the structural talks by early april after an 
additional meeting in march a final report is expected by summer 
</TEXT>
