<TEXT>
exxon corp on thursday lowered its fourth 
quarter and 1989 profit estimates by 300 million to account for 
legal costs and additional cleanup charges associated with last 
years alaska oil spill 
the revision marked the first time the worlds largest oil 
company has included litigation expenses in its spillrelated 
charges which now total more than 2 billion 
it also coincides with alaska attorney general douglas bailys 
disclosure that justice department and exxon attorneys might file a 
plea bargain settlement friday over pending criminal charges for 
environmental damages from the spill 
a dollar amount involved in a possible settlement has not been 
disclosed 
the additional charge announced thursday brings to 800 million 
the amount exxon deducted for outofpocket spillrelated expenses 
in the fourth quarter 
new developments and assessments led to the revised estimate 
of future costs associated with the valdez accident exxon said 
in a statement released late thursday 
spokesman bill smith declined to provide details except to say 
they were for past as well as anticipated litigation cleanup 
and environmental restoration expenses 
we havent broken it down smith said 
smith said the company did not know whether the company plans to 
add additional charges in 1990 for legal or other costs 
an exxon tanker that ran onto a reef last march 24 in alaskas 
prince william sound spilled 11 million gallons of crude oil 
fouling miles of shoreline and killing fish and other wildlife 
in addition to the charges there are 170 spillrelated lawsuits 
pending against exxon 
for the fourth quarter exxon estimates its earnings will total 
485 million or 37 cents a share down 65 percent from 14 
billion or 106 a share in the comparable 1988 period exxon 
earlier estimated fourthquarter profits of 785 million or 61 
cents a share 
revenue was up 15 percent in the quarter to 266 billion from 
23 billion 
for all of 1989 exxon revised its earnings estimate to 35 
billion or 274 a share from its earlier 38 billion or 298 
a share that was a 34percent drop from 53 billion or 395 a 
share in 1988 revenue was 961 billion compared with 886 
billion 
the latest provision comes on top of charges totaling 880 
million in the first and second quarters and more than 400 million 
in insurance proceeds that exxon has said it expected to have 
available to help pay for spillrelated cleanup costs 
exxon annnounced this week that it would return to alaska on may 
1 to clean up remnants of the spill exxons announcement followed 
a coast guard declaration essentially ordering the company to 
return 
although exxon has said it would continue the cleanup this 
spring it also has worried state and environmental officials by 
insisting that the wind and wave action would make cleaning 
unnecessary this summer 
