<TEXT>
for years the sterling image of wonderful 
service and quality merchandise at the nordstroms department store 
chain has been the envy of the retail industry and fueled 
expansion customer loyalty and high profits 
now that image has been tarnished by a state labor finding that 
the company doesnt properly compensate its sales force and by 
worker allegations the behind the quality service is oftengrueling 
pressure to produce sales 
but some shoppers say theyre not ready to stop buying at 
nordstrom even though their visits have become somewhat of a guilt 
trip 
i will probably still shop here because of their merchandise 
but i dont agree with the way they treat their employees said 
annette voeller a communications manager said outside nordstroms 
flagship seattle store 
i dont think ill stop shopping there but its nice to pay 
the employees said angela kristie a sportswear saleswoman at 
competitor frederick and nelson who passes up her 20 percent 
employee discount to buy shoes at nordstrom 
the state department of labor and industries last week found 
nordstrom systematically made employees perform workrelated duties 
without compensation and ordered it to pay them two years worth 
of overtime 
the finding stemmed from a complaint by the united food and 
commercial workers union which said clerks were expected to 
deliver merchandise to customers homes do inventories and attend 
company pep talks on their own time 
the union estimates workers in washington are owed up to 40 
million while california employees of the store are owed 300 
million 
their system fosters unfair labor practices illegal 
employment practices and a lack of due process for employees 
said joe peterson president of local 1001 
nordstrom issued a statement thursday saying it accepts full 
responsibility for any pressure employees have felt to perform 
these duties without pay spokeswoman kelley tormey said 
nordstrom already has given employees compensation claim forms 
and instituted a new policy in which employees sign special 
timesheets when they go on customer deliveries so that they get 
paid tormey said 
nordstrom is exploring whether one of the states findings 
regarding calculation of overtime was based on correct 
interpretation of the law said tormey 
its premature to talk about the size of the impact of the 
findings on the companys image she said were very very 
concerned 
the rulings come as the company is in contract negotiations with 
the union which claims to represent around 1400 of the 3000 
sales clerks in washington the last contract expired july 31 
the states findings have divided employees as well as shoppers 
while some complained of hours of unpaid work others saw the issue 
as a ploy to ensure the unions survival 
to make out that people are oppressed here is insane said 
david fehrenbacher a womens shoes salesman who says he works 
regular hours to pull 30000 a year before profitsharing 
its not too bad for just standing there selling shoes you 
dont need a college degree and you dont need a technical 
background fehrenbacher said 
whatever the outcome of the dispute it is likely to affect 
nordstroms profitability analysts said 
the conflict is being watched widely by retailers because of the 
industrywide trend toward reinstituting commission sales which 
was led by nordstrom nearly all nordstrom salespeople receive a 
base salary of 985 per hour plus commission 
nordstrom generates about 400 of retail sales per square foot 
of floorspace about twice the industry average sales help 
earnings are also about twice the industry average 
the companys pretax profit margin of about 85 percent annually 
is one of the highest in the highly competitive industry 
analysts said nordstroms profitability is enhanced by 
offtheclock work but that quantifying the amount is difficult 
however they said changing the commission system to compensate 
employees would be costly 
theres no doubt that the profitability is partly 
attributable to offtheclock work said carol palmer retail 
analyst with duff and phelps in chicago if a uniontype 
mentality takes over its the worst thing that could happen 
if the company alters its commissions policy due to the union 
dispute other retailers will adapt that to their own needs 
analysts said 
everyones going into commission programs i dont think the 
trend will be derailed there will be a correction in the 
commissions system and it will continue said pam stubing vice 
president with moodys investor service in new york 
but analysts and shoppers say norstrom also benefits from a 
strong merchandise lineup and its noquestionsasked returns policy 
nordstrom has 60 stores in washington oregon california 
alaska virginia and utah it plans 16 more including moving into 
illinois new jersey maryland minnesota indiana connecticut 
massachusetts and new york 
from its high of 4250 a share last summer nordstrom stock has 
dropped 35 percent in value closing thursday at 2925 a share 
forty percent of the stock is owned by members of the founding 
nordstrom family 
the stock stabilized wednesday after a twoday slide knocked 15 
percent off its value 
nordstroms stock also has been hurt by the companys 
announcement this week that fourthquarter earnings will be lower 
than a year earlier a decline would be the first since nordstrom 
went public 19 years ago and a marked reversal from analyst 
estimates of a 10 percent gain 
