<DOCNO> AP900222-0266 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the justice department and exxon corp are 
near agreement on settling possible criminal charges over last 
years massive alaska oil spill several sources said thursday 
but alaska officials said late thursday they would not endorse a 
tentative agreement outlined by the justice department and hoped 
improvements can still be made that would make it acceptable to the 
state 
under the proposed agreement the federal government would 
abandon its commitment to alaska to assist with its civil claims 
against exxon complained alaska attorney general douglas baily 
he told reporters that the justice department was trying to 
force the state to make a hasty endorsement of a plea 
bargaining agreement that amounted to little more than a pig in a 
poke and falls short of ensuring full restoration of damaged 
resources 
environmental groups and a congressman also called the plea 
bargaining inappropriate accusing the bush administration with 
pushing for a quick settlement that would allow exxon to escape 
more severe criminal penalties 
from all accounts the bush adminstration is giving exxon a 
wink and a nod a mere slap on the wrist said jay hair 
president of the national wildlife federation 
justice department spokesmen would only confirm that plea 
negotiations have been under way with exxon whose tanker exxon 
valdez released 11 million gallons of oil off alaska in prince 
william sound last march it was the countrys worst oil spill 
but several sources both in and out of the government all 
speaking on condition that they not be identified said a 
settlement could be announced as early as friday 
exxon announced thursday it was taking another charge against 
earnings of 300 million for litigation costs in connection with 
the spill bringing the companys total costs to more than 2 
billion 
the justice department talks with exxon were said to revolve 
around possible penalites of up to 500 million to be paid over a 
number of years by exxon into a natural resources restoration for 
prince william sound 
one source said that under the draft agreement exxon would have 
to pay only 150 million initially with the rest of the 500 
million spread over seven years with each payment subject to 
challenge by exxon 
if you read the fine print it could be substantially less in 
actual payments overall said the source who spoke on the 
condition that he not be identified 
in addition justice has sought a lesser criminal fine but the 
amount could not be learned thursday night 
exxon attorneys have tried to limit the amount of money they 
must pay directly to the us treasury as criminal penalties 
preferring to pay most of the penalties into the restoration fund 
sources said 
there was no answer at exxons offices in new york thursday 
evening earlier in the week company spokesmen declined to discuss 
the discussions with the justice department 
environmental lawyers said that money paid for restoration under 
the criminal settlement could be tax deductible as an ordinary cost 
of doing business and later may be used to reduce future 
assessements against exxon under various civil proceedings 
criminal penalties could not be deducted from future assessements 
nor would they be tax deductible 
under two criminal statutes used by federal prosecutors in oil 
spill cases fines of up to double the cost of the cleanup could be 
levied 
the administration is moving too quickly said mike matz of 
the sierra club and chairman of the alaska coalition a group of 
environmental and civic organizations 
exxon is responsible for the worst environmental tragedy since 
three mile island and the justice department wants to punish them 
with little more than a slap on the wrist 
bob adler a spokesman for the washingtonbased natural 
resources defense council said no settlement should be signed 
before the extent of longterm damages to natural resources is even 
known he said 500 million would be grossly inadequate 
in alaska state officials accused the justice department of 
abandoning their state 
if the latest draft of this agreement is imposed alaska would 
find itself on the short end of the stick we are being asked to 
accept a pig in a poke and that pig smells awfully bad said 
a statement issued by the offices of gov steve cowper and attorney 
general douglas baily 
meanwhile attorneys representing plaintiffs in civil suits 
against exxon filed a petition in federal court in anchorage asking 
that any plea bargaining agreement be subject to an open court 
hearing before becoming final 
rep george miller dcalif also criticized the justice 
department bargaining with exxon saying the agreement may not 
provide full damages and might jeopardize the rights of other 
parties seeking damages from exxon 
miller chairman of the house interior subcommittee on water 
power and offshore energy resources said the bush administration 
was moving too quickly 
the criminal investigation hasnt even reached the stage of 
indicting miller told reporters 
</TEXT>
